gf_ODR=26|ga_ODR=16\n|win_POS=8|draw_POS=6|loss_POS=6|gf_POS=32|ga_POS=30\n|win_KVA=8|draw_KVA=5|loss_KVA=7|gf_KVA=39|ga_KVA=31\n|win_MZA=8|draw_MZA=5|loss_MZA=7|gf_MZA=27|ga_MZA=22\n|win_VAR=8|draw_VAR=4|loss_VAR=8|gf_VAR=28|ga_VAR=22\n|win_\u017dEL=6|draw_\u017dEL=5|loss_\u017dEL=9|gf_\u017dEL=21|ga_\u017dEL=40|status_\u017dEL=O\n|win_OKT=0|draw_OKT=1|loss_OKT=19|gf_OKT=10|ga_OKT=96|status_OKT=R\n|col_P=green1|text_P = Promotion to [[1951 Yugoslav First League|Yugoslav First League]]\n|result1=P|result2=P|result3 = P|result4=P\n|col_RP=red2|text_RP=Qualification for relegation play-offs\n|result10=RP\n|col_R=red1|text_R=Relegation to Third Level\n|result11=R\n|update=complete\n|source=[http://www.fsgzrenjanin.com/Period%201944-1955.html fsgzrenjanin.com] \n|class_rules=1st points; 2nd goal average. \n}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[1950 Yugoslav First League]]\n\n{{Yugoslav Second League}}  \n\n[[Category:Yugoslav Second League seasons]]\n[[Category:1949\u201350 in European second tier association football leagues|Yugo]]\n[[Category:1949\u201350 in Yugoslavian football|2]]\n[[Category:1950\u201351 in European second tier association football leagues|Yugo]]\n[[Category:1950\u201351 in Yugoslavian football|2]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2013}}\n{{Infobox football league season\n| competition      = [[Yugoslav Second League]]\n| season           = 1950\n| winners          = [[NK Zagreb|Borac Zagreb]]\n| promoted         = [[NK Zagreb|Borac Zagreb]]<br/>[[FK Vojvodina|Sloga Novi Sad]]<br/>[[FK Napredak Kru\u0161evac|Napredak Kru\u0161evac]]<br/>[[FK Ma\u010dva \u0160abac|Podrinje \u0160abac]]\n| relegated        = [[FK Kumanovo|11 Oktomvri Kumanovo]]\n| league topscorer = \n| biggest home win = \n| biggest away win = \n| highest scoring  = \n| matches          = \n| total goals      = \n| prevseason       = [[1948\u201349 Yugoslav Second League|1948\u201349]]\n| nextseason       = [[1951 Yugoslav Second League|1951]]\n}}\n\nThe '''1950 [[Yugoslav Second League]] season''' was the 4th season of the Second Federal League (Croatian: ''Druga savezna liga'', Serbian: ''\u0414\u0440\u0443\u0433\u0430 \u0441\u0430\u0432\u0435\u0437\u043d\u0430 \u043b\u0438\u0433\u0430''), the second level [[association football]] competition of [[SFR Yugoslavia]], since its establishment in 1946.\n\n==Teams==\nA total of eleven teams contested the league, including five sides from the 1948\u201349 season, one club relegated from the [[1948\u201349 Yugoslav First League]] and five sides promoted from the third tier leagues played in the 1948\u201349 season. The league was contested in a [[double round robin]] format, with each club playing every other club twice, for a total of 20 rounds. Two points were awarded for a win and one point for draws.\n\n[[FK Vojvodina|Sloga Novi Sad]] were relegated from the 1948\u201349 Yugoslav First League after finishing in the 9th place of the league table, while 10th placed [[Circolo Sportivo Ponziana 1912|Ponziana Trieste]] stopped competing in the Yugoslav League system. The five clubs promoted to the second level were [[FK Kumanovo|11 Oktomvri Kumanovo]], [[NK Zagreb|Borac Zagreb]], [[HNK Rijeka|Kvarner]], [[FK Napredak Kru\u0161evac|Napredak Kru\u0161evac]] and [[FK \u017deljezni\u010dar Sarajevo|\u017deljezni\u010dar Sarajevo]].\n\n{{Location map+ |Yugoslavia |float=right |width=350 |caption=Locations of teams' home cities in the 1950 Yugoslav Second League |places=\n{{Location map~ |Yugoslavia |lat=43.583333 |long=21.316667 |label=[[Kru\u0161evac]] |position=left }}\n{{Location map~ |Yugoslavia |lat=42.135833 |long=21.718056 |label=[[Kumanovo]] |position=left }}\n{{Location map~ |Yugoslavia |lat=46.051389 |long=14.505556 |label=[[Ljubljana]] }}\n{{Location map~ |Yugoslavia |lat=45.255    |long=19.845    |label=[[Novi Sad]] |position=right }}\n{{Location map~ |Yugoslavia |lat=45.544937 |long=18.695705 |label=[[Osijek]] |position=left }}\n{{Location map~ |Yugoslavia |lat=45.339202 |long=14.380959 |label=[[Rijeka]] |position=right}}\n{{Location map~ |Yugoslavia |lat=43.8476   |long=18.3564   |label=[[Sarajevo]] |position=left}}\n{{Location map~ |Yugoslavia |lat=42        |long=21.433333 |label=[[Skopje]] |position=right }}\n{{Location map~ |Yugoslavia |lat=44.76     |long=19.69     |label=[[\u0160abac]] |position=right }}\n{{Location map~ |Yugoslavia |lat=45.816667 |long=15.983333 |label=[[Zagreb]] }}\n}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: left;\"\n!width=\"130\"| Team\n!width=\"120\"| Location\n!width=\"200\"| [[Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia#Federal subjects|Federal subject]] \n!width=\"90\"| Position<br />in 1948\u201349\n|-\n|[[FK Kumanovo|11 Oktomvri Kumanovo]]\n|[[Kumanovo]]\n|{{flag|SR Macedonia}}\n|{{N/A}}\n|-\n|[[NK Zagreb|Borac Zagreb]]\n|[[Zagreb]]\n|{{flag|SR Croatia}}\n|{{N/A}}\n|-\n|[[HNK Rijeka|Kvarner]]\n|[[Rijeka]]\n|{{flag|SR Croatia}}\n|{{N/A}}\n|-\n|[[NK Kusto\u0161ija Zagreb|Metalac Zagreb]]\n|[[Zagreb]]\n|{{flag|SR Croatia}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|<span style=\"display:none\">004</span>4th\n|-\n|[[FK Napredak Kru\u0161evac|Napredak Kru\u0161evac]]\n|[[Kru\u0161evac]]\n|{{flag|SR Serbia}}\n|{{N/A}}\n|-\n|[[NK Olimpija Ljubljana (1911\u20132004)|Odred Ljubljana]]\n|[[Ljubljana]]\n|{{flag|SR Slovenia}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|<span style=\"display:none\">006</span>6th\n|-\n|[[FK Ma\u010dva \u0160abac|Podrinje \u0160abac]]\n|[[\u0160abac]]\n|{{flag|SR Serbia}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|<span style=\"display:none\">005</span>5th\n|-\n|[[NK Osijek|Proleter Osijek]]\n|[[Osijek]]\n|{{flag|SR Croatia}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|<span style=\"display:none\">008</span>8th\n|-\n|[[FK Vojvodina|Sloga Novi Sad]]\n|[[Novi Sad]]\n|{{flagicon|SR Serbia}} [[Socialist Autonomous Province of Vojvodina|SAP Vojvodina]]\n|{{N/A}}\n|-\n|[[FK Vardar|Vardar]]\n|[[Skopje]]\n|{{flag|SR Macedonia}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|<span style=\"display:none\">007</span>7th\n|-\n|[[FK \u017deljezni\u010dar Sarajevo|\u017deljezni\u010dar Sarajevo]]\n|[[Sarajevo]]\n|{{flag|SR Bosnia and Herzegovina}}\n|{{N/A}}\n|}\n\n==League table==\n{{#invoke:sports table|main|style=WDL\n|res_col_header=QR\n|use_goal_ratio=y\n|winpoints=2\n\n|team1=NKZ|name_NKZ=[[NK Zagreb|Borac Zagreb]]\n|team2=SNS|name_SNS=[[FK Vojvodina|Sloga Novi Sad]]\n|team3=NKR|name_NKR=[[FK Napredak Kru\u0161evac|Napredak Kru\u0161evac]]\n|team4=POD|name_POD=[[FK Ma\u010dva \u0160abac|Podrinje \u0160abac]]\n|team5=ODR|name_ODR=[[NK Olimpija Ljubljana (1911\u20132004)|Odred]]\n|team6=POS|name_POS=[[NK Osijek|Proleter Osijek]]\n|team7=KVA|name_KVA=[[HNK Rijeka|Kvarner]]\n|team8=MZA|name_MZA=[[NK Kusto\u0161ija Zagreb|Metalac Zagreb]]\n|team9=VAR|name_VAR=[[FK Vardar|Vardar]]\n|team10=\u017dEL|name_\u017dEL=[[FK \u017deljezni\u010dar Sarajevo|\u017deljezni\u010dar]]\n|team11=OKT|name_OKT=[[FK Kumanovo|11 Oktomvri Kumanovo]]\n|win_NKZ=10|draw_NKZ=5|loss_NKZ=5|gf_NKZ=46|ga_NKZ=19|status_NKZ=C,P\n|win_SNS=10|draw_SNS=4|loss_SNS=6|gf_SNS=44|ga_SNS=16|status_SNS=P\n|win_NKR=9|draw_NKR=6|loss_NKR=5|gf_NKR=33|ga_NKR=22|status_NKR=P\n|win_POD=8|draw_POD=7|loss_POD=5|gf_POD=30|ga_POD=22|status_POD=P\n|win_ODR=8|draw_ODR=6|loss_ODR=6|gf_ODR=26|ga_ODR=16\n|win_POS=8|draw_POS=6|loss_POS=6|gf_POS=32|ga_POS=30\n|win_KVA=8|draw_KVA=5|loss_KVA=7|gf_KVA=39|ga_KVA=31\n|win_MZA=8|draw_MZA=5|loss_MZA=7|gf_MZA=27|ga_MZA=22\n|win_VAR=8|draw_VAR=4|loss_VAR=8|gf_VAR=28|ga_VAR=22\n|win_\u017dEL=6|draw_\u017dEL=5|loss_\u017dEL=9|gf_\u017dEL=21|ga_\u017dEL=40|status_\u017dEL=O\n|win_OKT=0|draw_OKT=1|loss_OKT=19|gf_OKT=10|ga_OKT=96|status_OKT=R\n|col_P = #D0F0C0|text_P = Promotion to [[1951 Yugoslav First League]]\n|result1 = P|result4 = P|result3 = P|result2 = P\n|col_RP=#FFE6E6|text_RP=Relegation play-offs\n|result10=RP\n|col_R=#FFCCCC|text_R=1951 Third Tier\n|result11=R\n|update=complete\n|source=[http://www.fsgzrenjanin.com/Period%201944-1955.html fsgzrenjanin.com] \n|class_rules=1st points; 2nd goal average. \n}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[1950 Yugoslav First League]]\n\n{{Yugoslav Second League}}  \n\n[[Category:Yugoslav Second League seasons]]\n[[Category:1949\u201350 in European second tier association football leagues|Yugo]]\n[[Category:1949\u201350 in Yugoslavian football|2]]\n[[Category:1950\u201351 in European second tier association football leagues|Yugo]]\n[[Category:1950\u201351 in Yugoslavian football|2]]\n", "name_user": "Jolicnikola", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLeague table", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1950_Yugoslav_Second_League"}
{"title_page": "Stefon", "text_new": "{{About|the ''Saturday Night Live'' character||Stefan (disambiguation){{!}}Stefan}}\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = Stefon Meyers\n| series             = [[Saturday Night Live]]\n| image              = Stefon, SNL Character.jpg\n| image_size         = 250px\n| caption            = Stefon on ''Weekend Update''\n| first              = November 1, 2008<ref name=\"SNL Archives | Episodes | Details\">[http://snl.jt.org/detail.php?i=2008110112 SNL Archives | Episodes | Details] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110726211439/http://snl.jt.org/detail.php?i=2008110112 |date=2011-07-26 }} \u2013 November 1, 2008</ref>\n| last               = May 18, 2013 (regular)<br/>March 17, 2018 (guest)\n| creator            = [[Bill Hader]]<br/>[[John Mulaney]]\n| portrayer          = Bill Hader<br/>[[Edward Norton]] (''[[Saturday Night Live 40th Anniversary Special|40th Anniversary Special]]'')\n| gender             = Male\n| occupation         = Correspondent for ''[[Saturday Night Live|SNL]]''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s ''[[Weekend Update]]''\n| title              = City Correspondent\n| family             = Ms. Stefon (mother)\n| spouse             = {{marriage|[[Seth Meyers]]|May 18, 2013}}\n| children           = Unnamed son (mentioned once)<br/>Unnamed children (with Meyers; mentioned during the ''SNL 40th Anniversary Special'')\n| relatives          = \n| religion           = \n| nationality        = [[United States|American]]\n}}\n\n'''Stefon Meyers''' (''[[married and maiden names|n\u00e9]]'' '''Zolesky'''),<ref>Season 38 Episode 21 (aired 5/18/2012)</ref> simply referred to as '''Stefon''', is a character played by [[Bill Hader]] on ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' who appeared as the New York City correspondent for ''[[Weekend Update]]'' with [[Seth Meyers]], created by Hader and former ''SNL'' writer [[John Mulaney]]. Meyers introduced Stefon as a guide who knows all about New York and asks him for tips on essential destinations and events for visitors. Stefon recommends unusual clubs and parties with bizarre characters and very specific tastes, described as \"visions a dying gay man would have if he was under too many blankets,\"<ref>Season 35 Episode 20 (aired 2/12/2011)</ref> \"nightmares of a crystal meth addict,\" or a \"coked-up gay [[Candyland]].\"<ref>Season 36, Episode 4; Weekend Update (10/23/2010)</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=How SNL's Bill Hader creates New York's weirdest nightclubs|url=http://www.dailydot.com/entertainment/snl-bill-hader-stefon-clubs-interview/|accessdate=April 17, 2015|work=Daily Dot|date=November 20, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Origin==\n\nStefon's segments were inspired by real people Hader and Mulaney had encountered. One was a club promoter who sent Mulaney an email about a club that \"had everything,\" including \"rooms full of broken glass\" as one of the highlights.<ref>{{cite news |title=Stefon, from \"S.N.L.,\" Is Real and Works in a New York Coffee Shop |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sAK15tZmSAM |accessdate=February 23, 2020 |work=The New Yorker Festival |date=Oct 20, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe character's mannerisms were based on a barista at a coffee shop in [[Chelsea, Manhattan]] that Hader frequented who looked and talked like Stefon.<ref name=\"test\">Potts, Kim (September 24, 2010) [http://www.tvsquad.com/2010/09/24/snl-star-bill-hader-talks-the-new-season-jon-hamms-return-an/ \"'SNL' Star Bill Hader Talks the New Season, Jon Hamm's Return and His 'Surreal Life' Experience with Corey Feldman\"]. ''[[The Huffington Post]]''.</ref> Mulaney decided that Stefon should wear an [[Don Ed Hardy|Ed Hardy]] shirt, under the assumption that it was made of latex and looked like something out of the Macaulay Culkin and Seth Green film, ''[[Party Monster (film)|Party Monster]]''. Stefon's hair was inspired by the characters in that film, \"specifically based in popup club culture in New York City circa 2007\".<ref name=\"behind\">{{cite web |title=Behind the Sketch: Stefon with John Mulaney - SNL |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_C14eXiZQWo |website=Saturday Night Live |accessdate=February 23, 2020 |date=April 14, 2018}}</ref> \n\n==Production==\nInitially, Stefon appeared in a 2008 sketch with [[Ben Affleck]] titled \"Movie Pitch with Stefon,\" with Stefon portraying the outrageous brother of Affleck's more serious character, David Zolesky; however, the idea \"barely worked as a sketch,\" said [[Bill Hader]]. \"It was a long walk to get to what the sketch was about.\"<ref name=\"origin\">{{cite web |title=Bill Hader on the Origin of Stefon |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=71Mm8RymCZw |website=Late Night with Seth Meyers |accessdate=February 23, 2020 |date=September 15, 2014}}</ref> \n\nThe  character was instead introduced as a correspondent on ''Weekend Update'' the following season, after an invitation from the head of the segment. According to [[Seth Meyers]], \"It was a lot easier to just say, 'Hey, here's Stefon.'\"<ref name=\"origin\"/> During the production for his first appearance on  ''Weekend Update'', on the April 24, 2010 episode, Mulaney assumed it would be cut after rehearsal. He stated, \"It was so weird that I so assumed it would be cut, and I said, 'When you cut this, can we try it again?' We just thought it was not going to be liked by anyone.\" However, the character became immensely popular.<ref name=\"behind\"/>\n\nOften Hader can be seen suppressing fits of laughter (known as [[corpsing]]), as some of the more outlandish descriptions are new to him. Hader, on late-night TV interviews, said that this happens with such frequency because changes are often made to the script up until the live show, and frequently Hader does not see the final cue cards until the live broadcast. As a result, some of the more outrageous things that Stefon says are relatively or completely new to Hader. \"I have not gotten through a single Stefon update without breaking,\" Hader says. \"Still working on it.\"<ref>Statdtmiller, Mandy. [http://www.nypost.com/p/entertainment/tv/club_kidding_TlEXRM3UWgo7E7OzKo5EwI#ixzz1Fgs6XTmQ Club kidding]. ''[[New York Post]]''. February 19, 2011. Retrieved May 21, 2012.</ref>\n\nAfter being unable to perform the character without breaking for two and a half years, Hader successfully remained in character as Stefon during the season finale of the show's [[Saturday Night Live (season 36)|36th season]], with host [[Justin Timberlake]]. However, this appearance was much briefer than his others, with his appearance only lasting about 30 seconds. According to Hader, it is \"completely ironic\" that he played a character like Stefon, because he avoids loud places such as clubs.<ref name=\"fallon20130905\">{{cite web | url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2013/09/05/bill-hader-is-sad-to-leave-saturday-night-live-and-stefon-behind.html | title=Bill Hader Is Sad to Leave \u2018Saturday Night Live\u2019 (and Stefon) Behind | work=The Daily Beast | date=2013-09-05 | accessdate=5 September 2013 | author=Fallon, Kevin}}</ref>\n\nStefon's last regular appearance on ''SNL'' was on May 18, 2013, owing to Bill Hader's leaving the show. As part of the ''Weekend Update'' comedy skit, Seth Meyers realized how much he actually loved Stefon and \"married\" him.\n\nWhen Meyers' ''[[Late Night with Seth Meyers|Late Night]]'' premiered on February 24, 2014, a Stefon [[matryoshka doll]] with a veil embellishment, originally hand-crafted by matryoshka artist Irene Hwang and commissioned for a crew holiday gift, was unveiled as part of the decor of Meyers' desktop.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.glamour.com/entertainment/blogs/obsessed/2014/02/the-late-night-with-seth-meyer.html|title=The Late Night With Seth Meyers Premiere: Fred Armisen, Amy Poehler, and a Tiny Stefon|last=Angelo|first=Megan|date=25 February 2014|magazine=[[Glamour (magazine)|Glamour.com]]|accessdate=9 March 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://bobobabushka.wordpress.com/2014/01/26/live-from-new-york/|title=Live From New York\u2026 |date=26 January 2014|work=[[WordPress.com]]|publisher=BoBo Babushka|accessdate=9 March 2014}}</ref>\n\nMulaney began writing a Stefon feature film before he left ''SNL''. The film was intended to be a [[mockumentary]], showing Stefon visiting different New York hotspots as a correspondent for ''Weekend Update''. Mulaney wanted to cast director [[Garry Marshall]] as [[Lorne Michaels]]. However, the film never moved beyond an initial writing stage.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wright |first1=Megh |title=John Mulaney and Seth Meyers Talk About the Stefon Movie That Never Got Made |url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/03/snl-john-mulaney-seth-meyers-stefon-movie.html |work=Vulture |date=March 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personality==\nStefon is a flamboyantly gay \"city correspondent\" for ''Weekend Update''. He appears to be always nervous, as indicated by how he can never keep his hands still and constantly rubs them together. Stefon always touches his face and hair, and it seems like he has frequent anxiety attacks. A possible explanation for this is his excessive consumption of recreational drugs.<ref name=\"test\"/> Stefon is very knowledgeable about parties and [[nightclub]]s featuring very bizarre themes and characters, which he recommends when host Seth Meyers asks for suggestions for tourists, much to Meyers' frustration. Stefon is apparently infatuated with Meyers; he expresses disappointment when Meyers mentions his girlfriend, and has stated that he envies Meyers' mother for changing his diapers as a child.\n\nAccording to the May 7, 2011, episode of ''Saturday Night Live'', his mother is named Ms. Stefon, and his father is [[David Bowie]]. In the October 20, 2012, episode, he mentions he has a dog named [[Mark Ruffalo|Bark Ruffalo]]. He lives in a trashcan outside the [[RadioShack]] at [[23rd Street (Manhattan)|23rd]] and [[Seventh Avenue (Manhattan)|7th]]. Stefon wears gaudy [[Don Ed Hardy|Ed Hardy]] shirts, multiple rings, and an asymmetrical, highlighted haircut.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Vineyard|first1=Jennifer|title=Bill Hader Would Totally Do a Stefon Bit at the CFDA Awards|url=http://nymag.com/thecut/2012/03/bill-hader-would-totally-do-a-stefon-bit-at-the-cfdas.html|accessdate=April 17, 2015|work=[[New York Magazine]]|date=March 16, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Format==\nStefon, the City Correspondent on ''Weekend Update'', is introduced by Seth Meyers and is asked for recommendations for tourists. Stefon's dialogue always begins with \u201cNew York\u2019s hottest club is \u2026\u201d and then he starts listing the outlandish patrons that you can meet at this club. He is frequently interrupted by Seth Meyers, who asks for more family-friendly destinations, but Stefon only continues talking about increasingly ludicrous New York clubs with suggestively descriptive names (Crease, Gush, Push, Booooooooof [\"with nine O's\"], Spicy, Kevin?, Whimsy, Your Mother and I Are Separating, PANTS!, et al.).\n\nSecurity, entertainers, and clientele at the venue are surreal, implied to be from hyper-specific or obscure subcultures, which an impressed Stefon usually introduces by complimenting \"this place has ''everything''\". Bouncers include: jacked-up homeless guys in period swimming costumes, Hobocops (homeless [[RoboCop (character)|RoboCops]]), a bulldog who looks like [[Wilford Brimley]], and a rabbi who looks like [[Joaquin Phoenix]]. Passwords for some of the clubs include \"My wallet? YEEEEAH, RIGHT!\" (\"the last words of murdered blues legend [[Blind Willie Walker|Sweet Willie Walker]]\") and \"Diabetes\" (said in a [[Wilford Brimley]] voice). When mentioning the club's typical patrons, he lists outlandish characters such as screaming babies in Mozart wigs, Puppets in disguise, an [[Albino]] who looks like [[Susan Powter]], Puppets practicing Karate, sunburned drifters with soap bubble beards, and groups of guys with afros in graduation caps. Underground celebrities to be found at the venues include Blingo (Black [[Ringo Starr|Ringo]]), [[Blacula|Jewish Dracula]] Sidney Applebaum, nine-year-old Tokyo pimp Ichi Yakaguro <ref name=\"test.,<ref name=\"test2\">Season 35, Episode 20 (aired 4/24/2010).</ref> and 300-pound Chinese baby deejay DJ Baby Bok Choy.<ref>\"''He's a giant 300-pound Chinese baby, who wears tinted aviator glasses and he spins records with his little ravioli hands.''\" Season 25, Episode 20, Retrieved (Jan 25, 2011).</ref>\n\nWhen describing the club\u2019s attractions, Stefon repeatedly uses vague faux pop culture [[portmanteau]]x and slang terms including \"Jewpids\" (Jewish Cupids), \"Furkels\" (fat [[Steve Urkel|Urkels]]) and \"[[Teddy Grahams|Teddy Graham]] people\" (\"...when a guy has the stumpy arms but with the belly\"). Stefon also frequently mentions objects personified by [[dwarfism|little people]] (\"human fanny packs,\" \"human traffic cones,\" \"human fire hydrants,\" \"human boomboxes,\" \"human suitcases,\" \"human kites\", \"human R2-D2s\", \"human pi\u00f1atas\", \"human Roombas\" (also called \"Hoombas\") and \"human Magic 8 balls.\"), which he originally referred to as \"midgets\". When Seth Meyers pointed out in one segment that the term \"midget\" was politically incorrect, Stefon corrected himself and referred to them as \"fun-sized\"; in a 2018 guest appearance alongside Colin Jost and Michael Che, Stefon brought his lawyer Shy (John Mulaney) onto the show to inform him that the correct term was \"little people\". The club owners Stefon describes are almost always malapropisms of famous celebrities' names, e.g., [[Susan Lucci|Snoozin Lucci]], [[Lou Diamond Phillips|Jew Diamond Phillips]], [[Anderson Cooper|Tranderson Cooper]], [[Tony Danza|Baloney Danza]], [[Pat Sajak|Fat Sajak]], [[Ray Liotta|Gay Liotta]], [[Faye Dunaway|Gay Dunaway]], [[Annie Oakley|Tranny Oakley]], [[Deepak Chopra|D-bag Chopra]], and [[O. J. Simpson|Blow J. Simpson]]. His style comes close to [[absurdist humor]], mocking New York City's notorious [[Club Kids|Club Kid scene]]. In the November 10, 2012 episode, hosted by [[Anne Hathaway]], Stefon did not appear, but Hathaway made a joking reference to playing him.\n\n==Final regular appearance and guest appearances==\n\nStefon made his last recurring ''[[Weekend Update]]'' appearance on [[Saturday Night Live (season 38)|Season 38 Episode 21]] on May 18, 2013. After Stefon's usual comment on \"New York's hottest club\", [[Seth Meyers]] again criticized his recommendations, making Stefon flee out of [[NBC Studios (New York)|NBC Studios]] to get married. Seeing the error of his ways, Seth goes after him to the wedding at the Marble Collegiate Church on [[Fifth Avenue]] only to find out that Stefon is marrying [[Anderson Cooper]]. Seth goes in after Stefon and takes him away from the wedding back to Studio 8H, where they proclaim their love for each other. The wedding guests included Black [[George Washington]] as the minister, a puppet in disguise ([[ALF (TV series)|ALF]] in a trenchcoat), human traffic cones and a human fire hydrant, HoboCops, Jewpids, infamous gay running back Blowjay Simpson, a group of guys with afros and graduation caps, grown men in wedding dresses, jacked homeless guys in period bathing suits, Gizblow the coked-up [[Gremlins|Gremlin]], Furkel (fat [[Steve Urkel]]), evil chef [[Wario]] [[Mario Batali|Batali]], Germfs (German [[The Smurfs|Smurfs]]), Sidney Applebaum the Jewish Dracula, a screaming geisha, Hanukkah cartoon character [[Dora the Explorer|Menorah the Explorer]], and DJ Baby Bok Choy. [[Ben Affleck]] makes a cameo appearance reprising his role as Stefon's brother, David Zolefsky.<ref>{{cite web|title=DAVID ZOLEFSKY SKETCHES|url=https://www.nbc.com/saturday-night-live/cast/ben-affleck-57976/character/david-zolefsky-101671|publisher=[[NBC]]|accessdate=April 17, 2015}}</ref> After they return to the studio, various Weekend Update characters including [[David Paterson]] ([[Fred Armisen]]), Jacob the Bar Mitzvah Boy ([[Vanessa Bayer]]), Drunk Uncle ([[Bobby Moynihan]]), [[Arianna Huffington]] ([[Nasim Pedrad]]), The Devil ([[Jason Sudeikis]]), Jean K. Jean ([[Kenan Thompson]]), [[Ann Romney]] ([[Kate McKinnon]]) and The Girl You Wished You Didn't Start a Conversation with at a Party ([[Cecily Strong]]) along with [[Amy Poehler]] congratulate them by throwing rice. Seth refers to them as Seth and Stefon Meyers and closes out ''Weekend Update''.\n\nStefon returned to the ''Weekend Update'' desk in a guest appearance along with [[Amy Poehler]] to wish Meyers good luck in his final ''Weekend Update'', as Meyers prepared to become the new host of ''[[Late Night (NBC)|Late Night]]''. Stefon's jokes included that the world (outside ''SNL'') \"has everything...\", such as homeless weightlifters that look like [[The Croods]], Japanese daredevil [[Yoko Ono|YOLO Ono]] and human [[Digital video recorder|DVR]]s, to which Stefon replied \"It's that thing where a midget sits on your TV and tells you what happened on ''[[Scandal (TV series)|Scandal]]''. And like a regular cable box, it goes down all the time\". Before Seth's final Weekend Update goodbye, he acknowledged Stefon as his husband. In this appearance, Hader again broke character after the human DVR joke.\n\nStefon returned to the show on the October 11, 2014 episode, hosted by Hader. In this appearance he recommended clubs for tourists interested in autumn in New York. He expressed shock at new ''Weekend Update'' hosts [[Colin Jost]] and [[Michael Che]], questioning how long he had been on anesthesia, before looking at their racial make-up and remarking \"one of each.\" The sketch was co-written by John Mulaney, who worked on it with Hader over Skype and texted new jokes to the writers to once again surprise Hader, who barely began the sketch before having to cover his face from laughing. Hader had particular trouble staying in character due to each club Stefon recommended including at the end of its list of features [[Dan Cortese]] (mispronounced \"Dan Cortez\" due to a misspelling on Mulaney's part).<ref>{{cite tweet |last=Mulaney |first=John |user=mulaney |date=October 12, 2014 |title=Sent to Rob Klein last night. Apologies for misspelling Cortese. They didn't tell Bill about any of it before air. |number=521384618507776000|access-date=April 15, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Gupta|first1=Prachi|title=John Mulaney's Dan Cortese line made Bill Hader break character|url=https://www.salon.com/2014/10/13/john_mulaneys_dan_cortez_line_sent_bill_hader_into_a_fit_of_giggles/|website=Salon|accessdate=April 15, 2018}}</ref> Stefon referenced his now-husband Meyers by explaining that he was at home \"practicing sitting behind a desk,\" and ended the sketch by announcing he was pregnant.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=otT53ANCfR4</ref>\n\nAs part of ''Saturday Night Live''{{'}}s [[Saturday Night Live 40th Anniversary Special|40th Anniversary Special]], [[Edward Norton]] appeared as Stefon during the special's 40th anniversary-themed [[Weekend Update]]. Feeling like Norton was failing his impression, Stefon appeared to try to guide him into doing the correct hand gestures. After that, Meyers appeared behind both Norton and Stefon and briefly mentioned their unnamed children.<ref name=\"Stefon40BuzzFeed\">{{cite web | url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/emilyorley/there-were-two-stefons-on-the-snl-40th-anniversary-show-and#.ha9X4ygom | title=There Were Two Stefons On The \"SNL\" 40th Anniversary Show And The World Almost Exploded | work=[[BuzzFeed]] | date=2015-02-16 | accessdate=16 February 2015 | author=Orley, Emily}}</ref><ref name=\"Stefon40Junkie\">{{cite web | url=http://junkee.com/edward-norton-and-bill-hader-are-twin-stefon-doppelgangers-for-snls-40th-anniversary/51164 | title=Edward Norton And Bill Hader Are Twin Stefon Doppelgangers For SNL\u2019s 40th Anniversary | work=Junkie | date=2015-02-16 | accessdate=16 February 2015 | author=McKinnon, Alex}}</ref>\n\nOn March 17, 2018, three years after his last appearance in ''SNL'', Stefon returned to the Weekend Update desk for a [[St. Patrick's Day]]-themed segment of his New York City recommendations, which included multiple references to [[90th Academy Awards|recent Academy Award-winning films]], Farrahchauns (leprechauns that look like [[Farrah Fawcett]]) and human squatty potties. Stefon, who usually uses the term \"midget\" to describe his bizarre recommendations, chose not to use it in order to not be insensitive and consulted his attorney and conceptual piss artist named Shy (played by [[John Mulaney]], who co-created Stefon) for a better term, ultimately using \"little people\". Mulaney caused Hader to crack up by whispering into his ear during his brief appearance, \"My girlfriend works at [[Yoshinoya|Yoshinoya Beef Bowl]].\"<ref>https://news.avclub.com/heres-what-john-mulaney-said-to-make-bill-hader-break-c-1823919709</ref> Stefon also made a reference to Meyers' [[Late Night with Seth Meyers#Recurring segments|''A Closer Look'']] segment at [[Late Night with Seth Meyers|''Late Night'']].\n\n==''Saturday Night Live'' appearances==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! width=\"150\"| Date\n! width=\"170\"| Host\n! width=\"550\"| Notes\n|-\n! colspan=\"3\"| [[Saturday Night Live (season 34)|Season 34]]\n|-\n|November 1, 2008\n|[[Ben Affleck]]\n|First appearance as a character in a sketch titled \"Movie Pitch with Stefon,\" with Affleck playing Stefon's brother, David Zolesky.<ref name=\"SNL Archives | Episodes | Details\"/>\n|-\n! colspan=\"3\"| [[Saturday Night Live (season 35)|Season 35]]\n|-\n|April 24, 2010\n|[[Gabourey Sidibe]]\n|First ''[[Weekend Update]]'' appearance.\n|-\n|May 15, 2010\n|[[Alec Baldwin]]\n|\n|-\n! colspan=\"3\"| [[Saturday Night Live (season 36)|Season 36]]\n|-\n|October 23, 2010\n|[[Emma Stone]]\n|\n|-\n|December 11, 2010\n|[[Paul Rudd]]\n|\n|-\n|December 18, 2010\n|[[Jeff Bridges]]\n|Sang a Christmas song with [[David Paterson]] ([[Fred Armisen|Armisen]]) and [[Snooki]] ([[Bobby Moynihan|Moynihan]]).\n|-\n|February 12, 2011\n|[[Russell Brand]]\n|\n|-\n|May 7, 2011\n|[[Tina Fey]]\n|Kisses [[Seth Meyers]] for the first time in this episode, on the cheek.\n|-\n|May 21, 2011\n|[[Justin Timberlake]]\n|Only appearance where Hader did not break character; his appearance lasted roughly 30 seconds.\n|-\n! colspan=\"3\"| [[Saturday Night Live (season 37)|Season 37]]\n|-\n|October 8, 2011\n|[[Ben Stiller]]\n|Stefon and [[Zoolander|Derek Zoolander]] ([[Ben Stiller|Stiller]]) promote a charity to help fat kids.\n|-\n|December 10, 2011\n|[[Katy Perry]]\n|Also appears in promos for this episode.\n|-\n|February 18, 2012\n|[[Maya Rudolph]]\n|Makes a cameo during Maya Rudolph's opening monologue.\n|-\n|March 10, 2012\n|[[Jonah Hill]]\n|Kisses Seth Meyers on the lips for the first time. [[Bill Hader]] breaks so hard he cries a little bit.\n|-\n|May 19, 2012\n|[[Mick Jagger]]\n|\n|-\n! colspan=\"3\"| [[Saturday Night Live (season 38)|Season 38]]\n|-\n|October 20, 2012\n|[[Bruno Mars]]\n|Also introduced Mars as the musical guest. Hader again breaks so hard that he cries.\n|-\n|March 9, 2013\n|Justin Timberlake\n|\n|-\n|May 18, 2013\n|Ben Affleck\n|Ben Affleck makes a cameo appearance reprising his role as Stefon's brother, David Zolesky. Stefon's appearance in this episode marked his last as a recurring character\n|-\n! colspan=\"3\"| [[Saturday Night Live (season 39)|Season 39]]\n|-\n|February 1, 2014\n|[[Melissa McCarthy]]\n| Stefon makes his first guest appearance along with [[Amy Poehler]] on Seth Meyers' final ''Weekend Update''.\n|-\n! colspan=\"3\"| [[Saturday Night Live (season 40)|Season 40]]\n|-\n|October 11, 2014\n|Bill Hader\n|Second guest appearance and Hader's first as SNL host. Stefon reveals he is pregnant.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/saturday-night-live-recap-bill-740179 |title='SNL' Recap: Bill Hader's Stefon Is Pregnant |magazine=The Hollywood Reporter |date=October 11, 2014 |first=Ryan |last=Gajewski |accessdate=October 12, 2014 }}</ref>\n|-\n|February 15, 2015\n|''[[Saturday Night Live 40th Anniversary Special|SNL 40th Anniversary Special]]''\n|Appeared alongside [[Edward Norton]], who was dressed as Stefon and doing an impression of him. Seth Meyers mentions their unnamed children.<ref name=\"Stefon40BuzzFeed\"/><ref name=\"Stefon40Junkie\"/>\n|-\n! colspan=\"3\"| [[Saturday Night Live (season 43)|Season 43]]\n|-\n|March 17, 2018\n|Bill Hader\n|Third guest appearance and Hader's second as SNL host. [[John Mulaney]], the co-creator of Stefon, appears as his personal lawyer, Shy.\n|}\n\n==Appearances outside ''Saturday Night Live''==\nIn December 2011, Hader (as Stefon) and Seth Meyers made an appearance at A Funny Affair for Autism benefit.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://splitsider.com/2011/12/stefon-offers-nightlife-advice-to-autism-charity-eventgoers |title=Stefon Offers Nightlife Advice to Autism Charity Eventgoers |publisher=SplitSider |date=December 7, 2011 |first=Hallie |last=Cantor |accessdate=October 14, 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vulture.com/2011/12/bill-hader-stefon-saturday-night-live.html |title=Bill Hader\u2019s Stefon Has Some Christmas Recommendations for You |publisher=Vulture |date=December 6, 2011 |first=Abby |last=Schreiber |accessdate=October 14, 2014 }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Recurring Saturday Night Live characters and sketches introduced 2008\u20132009|Recurring ''Saturday Night Live'' characters and sketches introduced 2008\u20132009]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120622183905/http://www.nbc.com/saturday-night-live/exclusives/stefon/ Stefon \u2013 SNL Exclusives]\n* [http://www.hulu.com/search?query=stefon&st=1&fs=null Hulu Video]\n* [[Entertainment Weekly|EW.com]]: [http://www.ew.com/article/2013/05/17/saturday-night-live-stefon-clubs-everything Complete list of Stefon's clubs]\n\n{{Saturday Night Live}}\n{{John Mulaney}}\n\n[[Category:Television characters introduced in 2008]]\n[[Category:Fictional gay males]]\n[[Category:Saturday Night Live characters]]\n[[Category:Fictional LGBT characters in television]]\n[[Category:Saturday Night Live in the 2000s]]\n[[Category:Saturday Night Live in the 2010s]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the ''Saturday Night Live'' character||Stefan (disambiguation){{!}}Stefan}}\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = Stefon Meyers\n| series             = [[Saturday Night Live]]\n| image              = Stefon, SNL Character.jpg\n| image_size         = 250px\n| caption            = Stefon on ''Weekend Update''\n| first              = November 1, 2008<ref name=\"SNL Archives | Episodes | Details\">[http://snl.jt.org/detail.php?i=2008110112 SNL Archives | Episodes | Details] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110726211439/http://snl.jt.org/detail.php?i=2008110112 |date=2011-07-26 }} \u2013 November 1, 2008</ref>\n| last               = May 18, 2013 (regular)<br/>March 17, 2018 (guest)\n| creator            = [[Bill Hader]]<br/>[[John Mulaney]]\n| portrayer          = Bill Hader<br/>[[Edward Norton]] (''[[Saturday Night Live 40th Anniversary Special|40th Anniversary Special]]'')\n| gender             = Male\n| occupation         = Correspondent for ''[[Saturday Night Live|SNL]]''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s ''[[Weekend Update]]''\n| title              = City Correspondent\n| family             = Ms. Stefon (mother)\n| spouse             = {{marriage|[[Seth Meyers]]|May 18, 2013}}\n| children           = Unnamed son (mentioned once)<br/>Unnamed children (with Meyers; mentioned during the ''SNL 40th Anniversary Special'')\n| relatives          = \n| religion           = \n| nationality        = [[United States|American]]\n}}\n\n'''Stefon Meyers''' (''[[married and maiden names|n\u00e9]]'' '''Zolesky'''),<ref>Season 38 Episode 21 (aired 5/18/2012)</ref> simply referred to as '''Stefon''', is a character played by [[Bill Hader]] on ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' who appeared as the New York City correspondent for ''[[Weekend Update]]'' with [[Seth Meyers]], created by Hader and former ''SNL'' writer [[John Mulaney]]. Meyers introduced Stefon as a guide who knows all about New York and asks him for tips on essential destinations and events for visitors. Stefon recommends unusual clubs and parties with bizarre characters and very specific tastes, described as \"visions a dying gay man would have if he was under too many blankets,\"<ref>Season 35 Episode 20 (aired 2/12/2011)</ref> \"nightmares of a crystal meth addict,\" or a \"coked-up gay [[Candyland]].\"<ref>Season 36, Episode 4; Weekend Update (10/23/2010)</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=How SNL's Bill Hader creates New York's weirdest nightclubs|url=http://www.dailydot.com/entertainment/snl-bill-hader-stefon-clubs-interview/|accessdate=April 17, 2015|work=Daily Dot|date=November 20, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Origin==\n\nStefon's segments were inspired by real people Hader and Mulaney had encountered. One was a club promoter who sent Mulaney an email about a club that \"had everything,\" including \"rooms full of broken glass\" as one of the highlights.<ref>{{cite news |title=Stefon, from \"S.N.L.,\" Is Real and Works in a New York Coffee Shop |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sAK15tZmSAM |accessdate=February 23, 2020 |work=The New Yorker Festival |date=Oct 20, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe character's mannerisms were based on a barista at a coffee shop in [[Chelsea, Manhattan]] that Hader frequented who looked and talked like Stefon.<ref name=\"test\">Potts, Kim (September 24, 2010) [http://www.tvsquad.com/2010/09/24/snl-star-bill-hader-talks-the-new-season-jon-hamms-return-an/ \"'SNL' Star Bill Hader Talks the New Season, Jon Hamm's Return and His 'Surreal Life' Experience with Corey Feldman\"]. ''[[The Huffington Post]]''.</ref> Mulaney decided that Stefon should wear an [[Don Ed Hardy|Ed Hardy]] shirt, under the assumption that it was made of latex and looked like something out of the Macaulay Culkin and Seth Green film, ''[[Party Monster (film)|Party Monster]]''. Stefon's hair was inspired by the characters in that film, \"specifically based in popup club culture in New York City circa 2007\".<ref name=\"behind\">{{cite web |title=Behind the Sketch: Stefon with John Mulaney - SNL |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_C14eXiZQWo |website=Saturday Night Live |accessdate=February 23, 2020 |date=April 14, 2018}}</ref> \n\n==Production==\nInitially, Stefon appeared in a 2008 sketch with [[Ben Affleck]] titled \"Movie Pitch with Stefon,\" with Stefon portraying the outrageous brother of Affleck's more serious character, David Zolesky; however, the idea \"barely worked as a sketch,\" said [[Bill Hader]]. \"It was a long walk to get to what the sketch was about.\"<ref name=\"origin\">{{cite web |title=Bill Hader on the Origin of Stefon |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=71Mm8RymCZw |website=Late Night with Seth Meyers |accessdate=February 23, 2020 |date=September 15, 2014}}</ref> \n\nThe  character was instead introduced as a correspondent on ''Weekend Update'' the following season, after an invitation from the head of the segment. According to [[Seth Meyers]], \"It was a lot easier to just say, 'Hey, here's Stefon.'\"<ref name=\"origin\"/> During the production for his first appearance on  ''Weekend Update'', on the April 24, 2010 episode, Mulaney assumed it would be cut after rehearsal. He stated, \"It was so weird that I so assumed it would be cut, and I said, 'When you cut this, can we try it again?' We just thought it was not going to be liked by anyone.\" However, the character became immensely popular.<ref name=\"behind\"/>\n\nOften Hader can be seen suppressing fits of laughter (known as [[corpsing]]), as some of the more outlandish descriptions are new to him. Hader, on late-night TV interviews, said that this happens with such frequency because changes are often made to the script up until the live show, and frequently Hader does not see the final cue cards until the live broadcast. As a result, some of the more outrageous things that Stefon says are relatively or completely new to Hader. \"I have not gotten through a single Stefon update without breaking,\" Hader says. \"Still working on it.\"<ref>Statdtmiller, Mandy. [http://www.nypost.com/p/entertainment/tv/club_kidding_TlEXRM3UWgo7E7OzKo5EwI#ixzz1Fgs6XTmQ Club kidding]. ''[[New York Post]]''. February 19, 2011. Retrieved May 21, 2012.</ref>\n\nAfter being unable to perform the character without breaking for two and a half years, Hader successfully remained in character as Stefon during the season finale of the show's [[Saturday Night Live (season 36)|36th season]], with host [[Justin Timberlake]]. However, this appearance was much briefer than his others, with his appearance only lasting about 30 seconds. According to Hader, it is \"completely ironic\" that he played a character like Stefon, because he avoids loud places such as clubs.<ref name=\"fallon20130905\">{{cite web | url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2013/09/05/bill-hader-is-sad-to-leave-saturday-night-live-and-stefon-behind.html | title=Bill Hader Is Sad to Leave \u2018Saturday Night Live\u2019 (and Stefon) Behind | work=The Daily Beast | date=2013-09-05 | accessdate=5 September 2013 | author=Fallon, Kevin}}</ref>\n\nStefon's last regular appearance on ''SNL'' was on May 18, 2013, owing to Bill Hader's leaving the show. As part of the ''Weekend Update'' comedy skit, Seth Meyers realized how much he actually loved Stefon and \"married\" him.\n\nWhen Meyers' ''[[Late Night with Seth Meyers|Late Night]]'' premiered on February 24, 2014, a Stefon [[matryoshka doll]] with a veil embellishment, originally hand-crafted by matryoshka artist Irene Hwang and commissioned for a crew holiday gift, was unveiled as part of the decor of Meyers' desktop.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.glamour.com/entertainment/blogs/obsessed/2014/02/the-late-night-with-seth-meyer.html|title=The Late Night With Seth Meyers Premiere: Fred Armisen, Amy Poehler, and a Tiny Stefon|last=Angelo|first=Megan|date=25 February 2014|magazine=[[Glamour (magazine)|Glamour.com]]|accessdate=9 March 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://bobobabushka.wordpress.com/2014/01/26/live-from-new-york/|title=Live From New York\u2026 |date=26 January 2014|work=[[WordPress.com]]|publisher=BoBo Babushka|accessdate=9 March 2014}}</ref>\n\nMulaney began writing a Stefon feature film before he left ''SNL''. The film was intended to be a [[mockumentary]], showing Stefon visiting different New York hotspots as a correspondent for ''Weekend Update''. Mulaney wanted to cast director [[Garry Marshall]] as [[Lorne Michaels]]. However, the film never moved beyond an initial writing stage.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wright |first1=Megh |title=John Mulaney and Seth Meyers Talk About the Stefon Movie That Never Got Made |url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/03/snl-john-mulaney-seth-meyers-stefon-movie.html |work=Vulture |date=March 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personality==\nStefon is a flamboyantly gay \"city correspondent\" for ''Weekend Update''. He appears to be always nervous, as indicated by how he can never keep his hands still and constantly rubs them together. Stefon always touches his face and hair, and it seems like he has frequent anxiety attacks. A possible explanation for this is his excessive consumption of recreational drugs.<ref name=\"test\"/> Stefon is very knowledgeable about parties and [[nightclub]]s featuring very bizarre themes and characters, which he recommends when host Seth Meyers asks for suggestions for tourists, much to Meyers' frustration. Stefon is apparently infatuated with Meyers; he expresses disappointment when Meyers mentions his girlfriend, and has stated that he envies Meyers' mother for changing his diapers as a child.\n\nAccording to the May 7, 2011, episode of ''Saturday Night Live'', his mother is named Ms. Stefon, and his father is [[David Bowie]]. In the October 20, 2012, episode, he mentions he has a dog named [[Mark Ruffalo|Bark Ruffalo]]. He lives in a trashcan outside the [[RadioShack]] at [[23rd Street (Manhattan)|23rd]] and [[Seventh Avenue (Manhattan)|7th]]. Stefon wears gaudy [[Don Ed Hardy|Ed Hardy]] shirts, multiple rings, and an asymmetrical, highlighted haircut.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Vineyard|first1=Jennifer|title=Bill Hader Would Totally Do a Stefon Bit at the CFDA Awards|url=http://nymag.com/thecut/2012/03/bill-hader-would-totally-do-a-stefon-bit-at-the-cfdas.html|accessdate=April 17, 2015|work=[[New York Magazine]]|date=March 16, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Format==\nStefon, the City Correspondent on ''Weekend Update'', is introduced by Seth Meyers and is asked for recommendations for tourists. Stefon\u2019s dialogue always begins with \u201cNew York\u2019s hottest club is \u2026\u201d and then he starts listing the outlandish patrons that you can meet at this club. He is frequently interrupted by Seth Meyers, who asks for more family-friendly destinations, but Stefon only continues talking about increasingly ludicrous New York clubs with suggestively descriptive names (Crease, Gush, Push, Booooooooof [\"with nine O's\"], Spicy, Kevin?, Whimsy, Your Mother and I Are Separating, PANTS!, et al.).\n\nSecurity, entertainers, and clientele at the venue are surreal, implied to be from hyper-specific or obscure subcultures, which an impressed Stefon usually introduces by complimenting \"this place has ''everything''\". Bouncers include: jacked-up homeless guys in period swimming costumes, Hobocops (homeless [[RoboCop (character)|RoboCops]]), a bulldog who looks like [[Wilford Brimley]], and a rabbi who looks like [[Joaquin Phoenix]]. Passwords for some of the clubs include \"My wallet? YEEEEAH, RIGHT!\" (\"the last words of murdered blues legend [[Blind Willie Walker|Sweet Willie Walker]]\") and \"Diabetes\" (said in a [[Wilford Brimley]] voice). When mentioning the club's typical patrons, he lists outlandish characters such as screaming babies in Mozart wigs, Puppets in disguise, an [[Albino]] who looks like [[Susan Powter]], Puppets practicing Karate, sunburned drifters with soap bubble beards, and groups of guys with afros in graduation caps. Underground celebrities to be found at the venues include Blingo (Black [[Ringo Starr|Ringo]]), [[Blacula|Jewish Dracula]] Sidney Applebaum, nine-year-old Tokyo pimp Ichi Yakaguro <ref name=\"test.,<ref name=\"test2\">Season 35, Episode 20 (aired 4/24/2010).</ref> and 300-pound Chinese baby deejay DJ Baby Bok Choy.<ref>\"''He's a giant 300-pound Chinese baby, who wears tinted aviator glasses and he spins records with his little ravioli hands.''\" Season 25, Episode 20, Retrieved (Jan 25, 2011).</ref>\n\nWhen describing the club\u2019s attractions, Stefon repeatedly uses vague faux pop culture [[portmanteau]]x and slang terms including \"Jewpids\" (Jewish Cupids), \"Furkels\" (fat [[Steve Urkel|Urkels]]) and \"[[Teddy Grahams|Teddy Graham]] people\" (\"...when a guy has the stumpy arms but with the belly\"). Stefon also frequently mentions objects personified by [[dwarfism|little people]] (\"human fanny packs,\" \"human traffic cones,\" \"human fire hydrants,\" \"human boomboxes,\" \"human suitcases,\" \"human kites\", \"human R2-D2s\", \"human pi\u00f1atas\", \"human Roombas\" (also called \"Hoombas\") and \"human Magic 8 balls.\"), which he originally referred to as \"midgets\". When Seth Meyers pointed out in one segment that the term \"midget\" was politically incorrect, Stefon corrected himself and referred to them as \"fun-sized\"; in a 2018 guest appearance alongside Colin Jost and Michael Che, Stefon brought his lawyer Shy (John Mulaney) onto the show to inform him that the correct term was \"little people\". The club owners Stefon describes are almost always malapropisms of famous celebrities' names, e.g., [[Susan Lucci|Snoozin Lucci]], [[Lou Diamond Phillips|Jew Diamond Phillips]], [[Anderson Cooper|Tranderson Cooper]], [[Tony Danza|Baloney Danza]], [[Pat Sajak|Fat Sajak]], [[Ray Liotta|Gay Liotta]], [[Faye Dunaway|Gay Dunaway]], [[Annie Oakley|Tranny Oakley]], [[Deepak Chopra|D-bag Chopra]], and [[O. J. Simpson|Blow J. Simpson]]. His style comes close to [[absurdist humor]], mocking New York City's notorious [[Club Kids|Club Kid scene]]. In the November 10, 2012 episode, hosted by [[Anne Hathaway]], Stefon did not appear, but Hathaway made a joking reference to playing him.\n\n==Final regular appearance and guest appearances==\n\nStefon made his last recurring ''[[Weekend Update]]'' appearance on [[Saturday Night Live (season 38)|Season 38 Episode 21]] on May 18, 2013. After Stefon's usual comment on \"New York's hottest club\", [[Seth Meyers]] again criticized his recommendations, making Stefon flee out of [[NBC Studios (New York)|NBC Studios]] to get married. Seeing the error of his ways, Seth goes after him to the wedding at the Marble Collegiate Church on [[Fifth Avenue]] only to find out that Stefon is marrying [[Anderson Cooper]]. Seth goes in after Stefon and takes him away from the wedding back to Studio 8H, where they proclaim their love for each other. The wedding guests included Black [[George Washington]] as the minister, a puppet in disguise ([[ALF (TV series)|ALF]] in a trenchcoat), human traffic cones and a human fire hydrant, HoboCops, Jewpids, infamous gay running back Blowjay Simpson, a group of guys with afros and graduation caps, grown men in wedding dresses, jacked homeless guys in period bathing suits, Gizblow the coked-up [[Gremlins|Gremlin]], Furkel (fat [[Steve Urkel]]), evil chef [[Wario]] [[Mario Batali|Batali]], Germfs (German [[The Smurfs|Smurfs]]), Sidney Applebaum the Jewish Dracula, a screaming geisha, Hanukkah cartoon character [[Dora the Explorer|Menorah the Explorer]], and DJ Baby Bok Choy. [[Ben Affleck]] makes a cameo appearance reprising his role as Stefon's brother, David Zolefsky.<ref>{{cite web|title=DAVID ZOLEFSKY SKETCHES|url=https://www.nbc.com/saturday-night-live/cast/ben-affleck-57976/character/david-zolefsky-101671|publisher=[[NBC]]|accessdate=April 17, 2015}}</ref> After they return to the studio, various Weekend Update characters including [[David Paterson]] ([[Fred Armisen]]), Jacob the Bar Mitzvah Boy ([[Vanessa Bayer]]), Drunk Uncle ([[Bobby Moynihan]]), [[Arianna Huffington]] ([[Nasim Pedrad]]), The Devil ([[Jason Sudeikis]]), Jean K. Jean ([[Kenan Thompson]]), [[Ann Romney]] ([[Kate McKinnon]]) and The Girl You Wished You Didn't Start a Conversation with at a Party ([[Cecily Strong]]) along with [[Amy Poehler]] congratulate them by throwing rice. Seth refers to them as Seth and Stefon Meyers and closes out ''Weekend Update''.\n\nStefon returned to the ''Weekend Update'' desk in a guest appearance along with [[Amy Poehler]] to wish Meyers good luck in his final ''Weekend Update'', as Meyers prepared to become the new host of ''[[Late Night (NBC)|Late Night]]''. Stefon's jokes included that the world (outside ''SNL'') \"has everything...\", such as homeless weightlifters that look like [[The Croods]], Japanese daredevil [[Yoko Ono|YOLO Ono]] and human [[Digital video recorder|DVR]]s, to which Stefon replied \"It's that thing where a midget sits on your TV and tells you what happened on ''[[Scandal (TV series)|Scandal]]''. And like a regular cable box, it goes down all the time\". Before Seth's final Weekend Update goodbye, he acknowledged Stefon as his husband. In this appearance, Hader again broke character after the human DVR joke.\n\nStefon returned to the show on the October 11, 2014 episode, hosted by Hader. In this appearance he recommended clubs for tourists interested in autumn in New York. He expressed shock at new ''Weekend Update'' hosts [[Colin Jost]] and [[Michael Che]], questioning how long he had been on anesthesia, before looking at their racial make-up and remarking \"one of each.\" The sketch was co-written by John Mulaney, who worked on it with Hader over Skype and texted new jokes to the writers to once again surprise Hader, who barely began the sketch before having to cover his face from laughing. Hader had particular trouble staying in character due to each club Stefon recommended including at the end of its list of features [[Dan Cortese]] (mispronounced \"Dan Cortez\" due to a misspelling on Mulaney's part).<ref>{{cite tweet |last=Mulaney |first=John |user=mulaney |date=October 12, 2014 |title=Sent to Rob Klein last night. Apologies for misspelling Cortese. They didn't tell Bill about any of it before air. |number=521384618507776000|access-date=April 15, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Gupta|first1=Prachi|title=John Mulaney's Dan Cortese line made Bill Hader break character|url=https://www.salon.com/2014/10/13/john_mulaneys_dan_cortez_line_sent_bill_hader_into_a_fit_of_giggles/|website=Salon|accessdate=April 15, 2018}}</ref> Stefon referenced his now-husband Meyers by explaining that he was at home \"practicing sitting behind a desk,\" and ended the sketch by announcing he was pregnant.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=otT53ANCfR4</ref>\n\nAs part of ''Saturday Night Live''{{'}}s [[Saturday Night Live 40th Anniversary Special|40th Anniversary Special]], [[Edward Norton]] appeared as Stefon during the special's 40th anniversary-themed [[Weekend Update]]. Feeling like Norton was failing his impression, Stefon appeared to try to guide him into doing the correct hand gestures. After that, Meyers appeared behind both Norton and Stefon and briefly mentioned their unnamed children.<ref name=\"Stefon40BuzzFeed\">{{cite web | url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/emilyorley/there-were-two-stefons-on-the-snl-40th-anniversary-show-and#.ha9X4ygom | title=There Were Two Stefons On The \"SNL\" 40th Anniversary Show And The World Almost Exploded | work=[[BuzzFeed]] | date=2015-02-16 | accessdate=16 February 2015 | author=Orley, Emily}}</ref><ref name=\"Stefon40Junkie\">{{cite web | url=http://junkee.com/edward-norton-and-bill-hader-are-twin-stefon-doppelgangers-for-snls-40th-anniversary/51164 | title=Edward Norton And Bill Hader Are Twin Stefon Doppelgangers For SNL\u2019s 40th Anniversary | work=Junkie | date=2015-02-16 | accessdate=16 February 2015 | author=McKinnon, Alex}}</ref>\n\nOn March 17, 2018, three years after his last appearance in ''SNL'', Stefon returned to the Weekend Update desk for a [[St. Patrick's Day]]-themed segment of his New York City recommendations, which included multiple references to [[90th Academy Awards|recent Academy Award-winning films]], Farrahchauns (leprechauns that look like [[Farrah Fawcett]]) and human squatty potties. Stefon, who usually uses the term \"midget\" to describe his bizarre recommendations, chose not to use it in order to not be insensitive and consulted his attorney and conceptual piss artist named Shy (played by [[John Mulaney]], who co-created Stefon) for a better term, ultimately using \"little people\". Mulaney caused Hader to crack up by whispering into his ear during his brief appearance, \"My girlfriend works at [[Yoshinoya|Yoshinoya Beef Bowl]].\"<ref>https://news.avclub.com/heres-what-john-mulaney-said-to-make-bill-hader-break-c-1823919709</ref> Stefon also made a reference to Meyers' [[Late Night with Seth Meyers#Recurring segments|''A Closer Look'']] segment at [[Late Night with Seth Meyers|''Late Night'']].\n\n==''Saturday Night Live'' appearances==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! width=\"150\"| Date\n! width=\"170\"| Host\n! width=\"550\"| Notes\n|-\n! colspan=\"3\"| [[Saturday Night Live (season 34)|Season 34]]\n|-\n|November 1, 2008\n|[[Ben Affleck]]\n|First appearance as a character in a sketch titled \"Movie Pitch with Stefon,\" with Affleck playing Stefon's brother, David Zolesky.<ref name=\"SNL Archives | Episodes | Details\"/>\n|-\n! colspan=\"3\"| [[Saturday Night Live (season 35)|Season 35]]\n|-\n|April 24, 2010\n|[[Gabourey Sidibe]]\n|First ''[[Weekend Update]]'' appearance.\n|-\n|May 15, 2010\n|[[Alec Baldwin]]\n|\n|-\n! colspan=\"3\"| [[Saturday Night Live (season 36)|Season 36]]\n|-\n|October 23, 2010\n|[[Emma Stone]]\n|\n|-\n|December 11, 2010\n|[[Paul Rudd]]\n|\n|-\n|December 18, 2010\n|[[Jeff Bridges]]\n|Sang a Christmas song with [[David Paterson]] ([[Fred Armisen|Armisen]]) and [[Snooki]] ([[Bobby Moynihan|Moynihan]]).\n|-\n|February 12, 2011\n|[[Russell Brand]]\n|\n|-\n|May 7, 2011\n|[[Tina Fey]]\n|Kisses [[Seth Meyers]] for the first time in this episode, on the cheek.\n|-\n|May 21, 2011\n|[[Justin Timberlake]]\n|Only appearance where Hader did not break character; his appearance lasted roughly 30 seconds.\n|-\n! colspan=\"3\"| [[Saturday Night Live (season 37)|Season 37]]\n|-\n|October 8, 2011\n|[[Ben Stiller]]\n|Stefon and [[Zoolander|Derek Zoolander]] ([[Ben Stiller|Stiller]]) promote a charity to help fat kids.\n|-\n|December 10, 2011\n|[[Katy Perry]]\n|Also appears in promos for this episode.\n|-\n|February 18, 2012\n|[[Maya Rudolph]]\n|Makes a cameo during Maya Rudolph's opening monologue.\n|-\n|March 10, 2012\n|[[Jonah Hill]]\n|Kisses Seth Meyers on the lips for the first time. [[Bill Hader]] breaks so hard he cries a little bit.\n|-\n|May 19, 2012\n|[[Mick Jagger]]\n|\n|-\n! colspan=\"3\"| [[Saturday Night Live (season 38)|Season 38]]\n|-\n|October 20, 2012\n|[[Bruno Mars]]\n|Also introduced Mars as the musical guest. Hader again breaks so hard that he cries.\n|-\n|March 9, 2013\n|Justin Timberlake\n|\n|-\n|May 18, 2013\n|Ben Affleck\n|Ben Affleck makes a cameo appearance reprising his role as Stefon's brother, David Zolesky. Stefon's appearance in this episode marked his last as a recurring character\n|-\n! colspan=\"3\"| [[Saturday Night Live (season 39)|Season 39]]\n|-\n|February 1, 2014\n|[[Melissa McCarthy]]\n| Stefon makes his first guest appearance along with [[Amy Poehler]] on Seth Meyers' final ''Weekend Update''.\n|-\n! colspan=\"3\"| [[Saturday Night Live (season 40)|Season 40]]\n|-\n|October 11, 2014\n|Bill Hader\n|Second guest appearance and Hader's first as SNL host. Stefon reveals he is pregnant.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/saturday-night-live-recap-bill-740179 |title='SNL' Recap: Bill Hader's Stefon Is Pregnant |magazine=The Hollywood Reporter |date=October 11, 2014 |first=Ryan |last=Gajewski |accessdate=October 12, 2014 }}</ref>\n|-\n|February 15, 2015\n|''[[Saturday Night Live 40th Anniversary Special|SNL 40th Anniversary Special]]''\n|Appeared alongside [[Edward Norton]], who was dressed as Stefon and doing an impression of him. Seth Meyers mentions their unnamed children.<ref name=\"Stefon40BuzzFeed\"/><ref name=\"Stefon40Junkie\"/>\n|-\n! colspan=\"3\"| [[Saturday Night Live (season 43)|Season 43]]\n|-\n|March 17, 2018\n|Bill Hader\n|Third guest appearance and Hader's second as SNL host. [[John Mulaney]], the co-creator of Stefon, appears as his personal lawyer, Shy.\n|}\n\n==Appearances outside ''Saturday Night Live''==\nIn December 2011, Hader (as Stefon) and Seth Meyers made an appearance at A Funny Affair for Autism benefit.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://splitsider.com/2011/12/stefon-offers-nightlife-advice-to-autism-charity-eventgoers |title=Stefon Offers Nightlife Advice to Autism Charity Eventgoers |publisher=SplitSider |date=December 7, 2011 |first=Hallie |last=Cantor |accessdate=October 14, 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vulture.com/2011/12/bill-hader-stefon-saturday-night-live.html |title=Bill Hader\u2019s Stefon Has Some Christmas Recommendations for You |publisher=Vulture |date=December 6, 2011 |first=Abby |last=Schreiber |accessdate=October 14, 2014 }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Recurring Saturday Night Live characters and sketches introduced 2008\u20132009|Recurring ''Saturday Night Live'' characters and sketches introduced 2008\u20132009]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120622183905/http://www.nbc.com/saturday-night-live/exclusives/stefon/ Stefon \u2013 SNL Exclusives]\n* [http://www.hulu.com/search?query=stefon&st=1&fs=null Hulu Video]\n* [[Entertainment Weekly|EW.com]]: [http://www.ew.com/article/2013/05/17/saturday-night-live-stefon-clubs-everything Complete list of Stefon's clubs]\n\n{{Saturday Night Live}}\n{{John Mulaney}}\n\n[[Category:Television characters introduced in 2008]]\n[[Category:Fictional gay males]]\n[[Category:Saturday Night Live characters]]\n[[Category:Fictional LGBT characters in television]]\n[[Category:Saturday Night Live in the 2000s]]\n[[Category:Saturday Night Live in the 2010s]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFormat:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stefon"}
{"title_page": "2020 Labour Party leadership election", "text_new": "{{for|the Labour Party (Ireland) election|2020 Labour Party leadership election (Ireland)}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{short description|British Labour Party leadership election}}\n{{Infobox election\n| election_name = {{nowrap|2020 Labour Party leadership election}}\n| type = presidential\n| ongoing = yes\n| previous_election = 2016 Labour Party leadership election (UK)\n| previous_year = 2016\n| next_election = \n| next_year = \n| turnout = \n| election_date = {{Start and end dates|2020|02|24|2020|04|04|df=yes}}\n\n<!-- PLEASE DO NOT REORDER WITHOUT CONSENSUS ON TALK PAGE - nomination numbers are not a vote -->\n\n<!-- Rebecca Long-Bailey -->| image1 = Official portrait of Rebecca Long Bailey crop 2.jpg\n| image1_size = 160x160px\n| candidate1 = [[Rebecca Long-Bailey]]\n| colour1 = \n| popular_vote1 = \n| percentage1 = \n\n<!-- Lisa Nandy -->| image2 = Official portrait of Lisa Nandy crop 2.jpg\n| image2_size = 160x160px\n| candidate2 = [[Lisa Nandy]]\n| colour2 = \n| popular_vote2 = \n| percentage2 = \n\n<!-- Keir Starmer -->| image3 = Official portrait of Keir Starmer crop 2.jpg\n| image3_size = 160x160px\n| candidate3 = [[Keir Starmer]]\n| colour3 = \n| popular_vote3 = \n| percentage3 = \n\n| title = leader\n| before_election = [[Jeremy Corbyn]]\n| after_election = \n}}\nThe '''2020 Labour Party leadership election''' was triggered after [[Jeremy Corbyn]] announced his intention to resign as [[Leader of the Labour Party (UK)|leader]] of the UK's [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] following the party's defeat at the [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019 general election]]. It is being held alongside the [[2020 Labour Party deputy leadership election]].\n\nTo qualify for the ballot, candidates needed nominations from 10% (22) of the party's [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Members of Parliament]] (MPs) and [[Member of the European Parliament|Members of European Parliament]] (MEPs), followed by support from either 5% (33) of [[Constituency Labour Party|Constituency Labour Parties]] (CLPs), or from at least three affiliated groups, including two trades unions and representing at least 5% of affiliated members.\n\nFive candidates, [[Rebecca Long-Bailey]], [[Lisa Nandy]], [[Jess Phillips]], [[Keir Starmer]] and [[Emily Thornberry]] received sufficient nominations to proceed to the second round of nominations. Starmer had the most nominations from MPs and MEPs at 88, followed by Long-Bailey and Nandy with 33 and 31 nominations respectively. Phillips and Thornberry each received 23 nominations, one above the minimum threshold to proceed. \n\nThree candidates, Long-Bailey, Nandy and Starmer, received sufficient combined support from affiliates and constituency parties to proceed to the final ballot. Starmer received the most nominations from both CLPs and affiliates having received nominations from 374 CLPs and 15 affiliates, followed by Long-Bailey with 164 CLPs and seven affiliates, and finally Nandy with 72 CLPs and four affiliates.\n\n==Background==\n{{also|Labour Party leadership of Jeremy Corbyn}}\n[[Jeremy Corbyn]] was elected Labour Party leader in a [[2015 Labour Party leadership election (UK)|2015 leadership election]] and [[2016 Labour Party leadership election (UK)|re-elected leader in 2016]] after a challenge from [[Owen Smith]]. While Labour gained 30 seats in the [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017 general election]], it lost 60 seats in the [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019 election]], resulting in the party having its lowest number of seats in the [[House of Commons (United Kingdom)|House of Commons]] since [[1935 United Kingdom general election|1935]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.channel4.com/news/factcheck/factcheck-the-2019-general-election-explained-in-five-graphs|title=The 2019 general election explained in five graphs|first=Georgina|last=Lee|date=13 December 2019|work=Channel 4 News|accessdate=16 January 2020|department=FactCheck}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/uk/john-mcdonnell-to-quit-frontline-politics-following-labour-defeat-38784856.html|title=John McDonnell to quit frontline politics following Labour defeat|first=Sophie|last=Morris|date=13 December 2019|accessdate=16 January 2020|work=Belfast Telegraph}}</ref> Corbyn subsequently announced that he would resign as Labour Party leader after a \"process of reflection\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/election-2019-50766114|title=Jeremy Corbyn: 'I will not lead Labour at next election'|date=13 December 2019|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/entry/jeremy-corbyn-resigns-labour-leader-general-election-2019_uk_5df2fcbce4b04bcba181d10b|title=Jeremy Corbyn Announces He Will Resign As Labour Party Leader|first=Ned|last=Simons|date=13 December 2019|work=HuffPost UK|accessdate=13 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Procedure==\nThe election is being conducted under a pure [[one member, one vote]] (OMOV) system, using the [[instant-runoff voting]] electoral system with preferential balloting to calculate the result.<ref name=\"next leader\" /><ref name=\"Politics-rules\"/> Candidates will be elected by members and registered and affiliated supporters, who all receive a maximum of one vote, and all votes will be weighted equally. This means that, for example, members of Labour-affiliated trades unions need to register as affiliated Labour supporters to vote.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jul/10/labours-leadership-contest-what-do-the-rules-look-like|title=Labour leadership contest: what are the rules?|work=The Guardian|last=Elgot|first=Jessica|date=10 July 2016|accessdate=12 July 2016}}</ref> Members who joined before 20 January will be eligible to vote.<ref name=\"Politics-rules\">{{cite web|url=http://www.politics.co.uk/comment-analysis/2019/12/16/labour-leadership-election-who-can-vote-and-how-does-it-work|title=Labour leadership election: Who can vote and how does it work?|first=Luke|last=Akehurst|work=Politics.co.uk|date=16 December 2019|access-date=16 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nTo stand, candidates needed to be nominated by at least 10% of the combined membership of the [[Parliamentary Labour Party]] (PLP) and [[European Parliamentary Labour Party]] (EPLP), meaning 22 MPs and MEPs at the time. As a result, a maximum of nine candidates can stand. They also needed to be nominated by at least 5% of [[Constituency Labour Party|Constituency Labour Parties]] (CLPs), meaning at least 33 CLPs, or at least three party affiliates that consist of at least 5% of affiliate members including at least two trades unions.<ref name=\"next leader\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-50781341|title=Who will be Labour's next leader?|date=13 December 2019|publisher=BBC News|access-date=13 December 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"NS-rules\">{{cite web|url=https://www.newstatesman.com/politics/elections/2019/12/how-does-labour-leadership-election-work|title=How does the Labour leadership election work?|work=New Statesman|date=13 December 2019|access-date=13 December 2019|last=Bush|first=Stephen}}</ref> Affiliates consist of [[Labour Party (UK) affiliated trade union|affiliated trades unions]], [[Socialist society (Labour Party)|socialist societies]] and the [[Co-operative Party]].<ref name=\"NS-rules\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.instituteforgovernment.org.uk/explainers/labour-party-leadership-contests|title=Labour Party leadership contests|publisher=Institute for Government|access-date=14 January 2020|author1=Zodgekar, Ketaki|author2=Durrant, Tim|date=6 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe timetable for the election was set by the party's [[National Executive Committee]] (NEC) on 6 January 2020.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/live/2020/jan/06/labour-leadership-jess-phillips-clarifies-brexit-stance-saying-she-cant-see-party-backing-remain-at-next-election-live-news|title=Labour leadership: NEC decides contest to last three months, with result announced Saturday 4 April \u2013 live news|last=Sparrow|first=Andrew|date=6 January 2020|work=The Guardian|access-date=6 January 2020|last2=Carrell|first2=Severin|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nNominations from the [[Parliamentary Labour Party]] and [[European Parliamentary Labour Party]] opened on 7 January and closed on 13 January. Between 15 January and 15 February, [[Constituency Labour Party|constituency parties]] and affiliate organisations could nominate their preferred candidate. Applications to become a registered supporter opened on 14 January and closed on 16 January. Voting in the membership ballot opened on 24 February<ref>{{cite news|url=https://labourlist.org/2020/02/ballot-drop-delays-tv-debates-and-fresh-policies-labours-leadership-latest/| title=Ballot drop delays, TV debates and fresh policies \u2013 Labour\u2019s leadership latest|last=Rodgers|first=Sienna|date=6 February 2020|work=LabourList|accessdate=19 February 2019}}</ref> and closed at midday on 2 April. The result of the leadership election will be announced on 4 April.<ref name=\"4 April\"/> The [[party conference|special conference]] planned for the announcement of the election result was \"scaled-back\" on 12 March because of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Labour leadership announcement cancelled |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-parliaments-51860609 |accessdate=13 March 2020 |publisher=BBC News |date=12 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Campaign==\n===Announcements===\nImmediately following the 2019 general election, [[Keir Starmer]], the [[Shadow Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union]], was considered favourite to win the leadership election by the online gambling company [[Betfair]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/politics/who-next-labour-leader-runners-21087938| title=Runners and riders to replace Jeremy Corbyn as the next Labour leader|last=Smith|first=Mikey|date=13 December 2019|work=Mirror Online |accessdate=13 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/next-labour-leader-odds-who-will-replace-jeremy-corbyn-a4312901.html|title=Next Labour leader odds: Who will replace Jeremy Corbyn?|author= Brewis, Harriet|date=13 December 2019|work=Evening Standard|accessdate=13 December 2019}}</ref> [[Rebecca Long-Bailey]], the shadow business secretary, was considered another front runner.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.brisbanetimes.com.au/world/europe/jeremy-corbyn-to-resign-amid-devastating-uk-election-defeat-20191213-p53jlt.html|title=Jeremy Corbyn steps down amid devastating UK election defeat|last=Shields|first=Bevan|date=13 December 2019|work=Brisbane Times|access-date=13 December 2019}}</ref> Various other figures were considered as possible leadership candidates, including [[Lisa Nandy]], the MP for [[Wigan (UK Parliament constituency)|Wigan]], who said on 15 December 2019 that she was \"seriously thinking\" about running for the leadership.<ref name= Honeycombe-Foster/> On 29 December, Long-Bailey wrote an article for ''[[The Guardian]]'' declaring her interest in standing and laying out her strategy for a \"progressive patriotism\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2019/dec/29/rebecca-long-bailey-labour-party-britain|title=We can take the Labour party back into power. Here's how|first=Rebecca|last=Long-Bailey|date=29 December 2019|work=The Guardian|accessdate=6 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nSome party figures, including the former MP [[Caroline Flint]] and the MP [[Wes Streeting]], argued for a \"clean break\" from the previous leadership. However, [[Len McCluskey]], general secretary of [[Unite the Union]],  said that the next leader should \"carry on the tradition\", describing Long-Bailey and [[Angela Rayner]] as his preferred candidates.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/election-2019-50800997|title=Let the Labour leadership battle commence|last=Pienaar|first=John|date=15 December 2019|publisher=BBC News|access-date=15 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/labour-leadership-contest-corbyn-rebecca-long-bailey-emily-thornberry-a9247966.html| title=Labour leadership race threatens party civil war as MPs fear 'continuity Corbyn' figure|date=15 December 2019|access-date=15 December 2019|author1= Woodcock, Andrew|author2= Buchan, Lizzie|work=The Independent}}</ref> Party figures affiliated with Long-Bailey and MPs such as Corbyn, as well as centrist figures like [[Alastair Campbell]], encouraged supporters of their preferred candidates to join the party to vote in the leadership election.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cityam.com/labours-period-of-reflection-quickly-turns-into-heated-leadership-race/|title=Labour's period of reflection quickly turns into leadership race|first=Stefan|last=Boscia|date=15 December 2019|work=City AM|access-date=15 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/labour-party-jeremy-corbyn-general-election-jess-phillips-a4313736.html|author= Christian, Bonnie|title=Labour moderates plan influx of new members to 'rebuild' party|date=15 December 2019|work=Evening Standard|access-date=15 December 2019}}</ref> [[Roy Hattersley]], a former deputy leader of the party, wrote on 21 December that MPs should refuse to accept Long-Bailey if she were elected leader.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/dec/21/david-lammy-may-stand-labour-first-bame-leader|title=Lammy hints at bid to be Labour's first BAME leader|last=Helm|first=Toby|date=21 December 2019|work=The Observer|access-date=21 December 2019|via=The Guardian}}</ref>\n\nThe shadow foreign secretary, [[Emily Thornberry]], was the first to announce, on 18 December, that she was standing for the leadership.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.sky.com/story/emily-thornberry-enters-contest-to-replace-labour-leader-jeremy-corbyn-11889772|title=Emily Thornberry enters contest to replace Labour leader Jeremy Corbyn|publisher=Sky News|author= Heffer, Greg|date = 18 December 2019|access-date=19 December 2019}}</ref> She laid out her pitch in an article for ''[[The Guardian]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2019/dec/18/boris-johnson-labour-brexit-election-emily-thornberry|title=Labour gifted Boris Johnson his 'Brexit election'. We can't be so inept again|author=Thornberry, Emily|date=18 December 2019|work=The Guardian|accessdate=6 January 2020}}</ref> She said that her first priority would be to deal with [[Antisemitism in the UK Labour Party|antisemitism in the party]] by implementing recommendations from the [[Board of Deputies of British Jews]], the [[Jewish Labour Movement]] and the [[Equality and Human Rights Commission]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/jan/09/thornberry-corbyn-aides-dismissed-attacks-against-israeli-civilians|title=Thornberry: Corbyn aides dismissed attacks against Israeli civilians |last=Syal|first=Rajeev|date=9 January 2020|work=The Guardian|access-date=10 January 2020|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> She criticised Corbyn's senior advisers for overruling her as the [[Shadow Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs|shadow foreign secretary]] and for their strategic decisions in the 2019 general election.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://politicshome.com/news/uk/political-parties/labour-party/jeremy-corbyn/news/108762/emily-thornberry-attacks-jeremy|author= Schofield, Kevin|title=Emily Thornberry attacks Jeremy Corbyn advisers as she steps up Labour leadership bid|date=24 December 2019|work=PoliticsHome|access-date=13 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url= https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/emily-thornberry-i-would-be-best-labour-leader-to-defeat-boris-johnson-qjchk80nn|title=Emily Thornberry: I would be best Labour leader to defeat Boris Johnson |last3=Elliott|first3=Francis |first1=Oliver|last1=Wright |first2=Henry|last2=Zeffman |date=19 December 2019|work=The Times |access-date=10 January 2020|issn=0140-0460}} {{subscription}}</ref>\n\n[[Clive Lewis (politician)|Clive Lewis]], the shadow minister for sustainable economics, announced on 19 December that he would stand.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.sky.com/story/clive-lewis-joins-emily-thornberry-in-labour-leadership-contest-to-replace-jeremy-corbyn-11890839|author= Snuggs, Tania|title=Clive Lewis joins Emily Thornberry in Labour leadership contest to replace Jeremy Corbyn|publisher=Sky News|date= 20 December 2019|access-date=13 January 2020}}</ref> He said that as leader, he would give more democratic power in the party to its members.<ref>{{Cite news| url= https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/i-ll-give-labour-members-more-say-clive-lewis-throws-his-hat-in-stn66056q|title=I'll give Labour members more say: Clive Lewis throws his hat in|last=Zeffman|first=Henry|date=20 December 2019|work=The Times|access-date=10 January 2020 |issn=0140-0460}} {{subscription}}</ref> He argued that the party should work more with other political parties on the left, and proposed constitutional reforms including supporting [[proportional representation]] and [[reform of the House of Lords]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/jan/07/clive-lewis-to-beat-tories-labour-has-to-work-with-other-progressives|title=Clive Lewis: to beat Tories, Labour has to work with other progressives|last=Stewart|first=Heather|date=7 January 2020|work=The Guardian|access-date=10 January 2020|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://inews.co.uk/news/politics/clive-lewis-labour-leadership-candidates-pitch-monarchy-referendum-proportional-representation-1361933|author= Chaplain, Chloe|title=Clive Lewis's radical leadership pitch includes a referendum on the monarchy|work=i News|date = 10 January 2020|access-date=10 January 2020}}</ref> In January 2020, he proposed a referendum about the future of the [[British royal family]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-51062770|title=Labour's Lewis calls for Royal Family referendum|date=10 January 2020|publisher=BBC News|access-date=10 January 2020}}</ref> He was criticised for his response to claims against him of sexual harassment, for which he had been cleared by a disciplinary body within Labour, which \"seemed unapologetic\".<ref>{{Cite news| url= https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/aides-fear-clumsy-response-to-abuse-claims-rules-out-clive-lewis-wbth3nt8f|title=Aides fear 'clumsy' response to abuse claims rules out Clive Lewis| last=Pogrund|first=Gabriel| date=5 January 2020|work=The Sunday Times|access-date=10 January 2020|via=The Times}} {{subscription}}</ref>\n\n[[Jess Phillips]] announced her candidacy in [[Grimsby]] on 3 January 2020.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-50981713|title=Jess Phillips joins Labour leadership race|date=3 January 2020|publisher=BBC News|access-date=3 January 2020}}</ref> She criticised the party's approach to Brexit and [[Scottish independence]], saying that she was opposed to a second referendum on Scottish independence.<ref name=\"Scottish independence\">{{cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/jess-phillips-says-no-to-another-scottish-independence-referendum-vvbdrdzzt|title=Jess Phillips opposes another Scottish independence referendum|last=McLaughlin|first=Mark|date=8 January 2020|work=The Times|access-date=10 January 2020|issn=0140-0460}} {{subscription}}</ref> She said that she would be open to arguing for the UK to rejoin the [[European Union]].<ref>{{cite news| url= https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/jan/05/labour-leadership-jess-phillips-says-party-could-argue-to-rejoin-eu|title=Labour leadership: Jess Phillips says party could argue to rejoin EU|last=Stewart|first=Heather|date=5 January 2020|work=The Guardian|access-date=10 January 2020|issn=0261-3077}} </ref><ref name=\":1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/jess-phillips-willing-to-fight-for-britain-to-rejoin-eu-w7f86xbh0|title=Jess Phillips willing to fight for Britain to rejoin EU|last=Swinford|first=Steven|date=5 January 2020|work=The Sunday Times|access-date=10 January 2020|issn=0956-1382|via=The Times}} {{subscription}}</ref> Criticising the party's manifesto at the 2019 general election, Phillips said that she would support nationalising railways but would not prioritise further nationalisation.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nNandy announced that she would stand in a letter to the ''[[Wigan Post]]'' on the same day as Phillips.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wigantoday.net/news/politics/exclusive-wigan-mp-lisa-nandy-enters-the-race-to-become-new-leader-of-the-labour-party-1-10181778|title=Wigan MP Lisa Nandy enters the race to become new Leader of the Labour Party|author= Nowell, Andrew|work=Wigan Today|date = 3 January 2020 |access-date=3 January 2020}}</ref> She argued that the party needed a \"bridge\" to join areas in [[northern England]] where the party was losing seats and metropolitan areas where the party was gaining support.<ref name= Honeycombe-Foster>{{cite news|url=https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/political-parties/labour-party/news/108575/lisa-nandy-reveals-she-seriously-considering-run|title=Lisa Nandy reveals she is 'seriously considering' run for Labour leadership|last=Honeycombe-Foster|first=Matt|date=15 December 2019|work=PoliticsHome|access-date=14 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nStarmer, who a poll had indicated was the most popular potential candidate heading into the leadership election, announced his candidacy with a video posted to social media on 4 January followed by a launch in [[Stevenage]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-50995782|title=Keir Starmer enters Labour leadership contest|date=4 January 2020|publisher=BBC News|access-date=4 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/jan/04/keir-starmer-enters-labour-leadership-race|title=Keir Starmer to launch Labour leadership bid in Stevenage|agency=PA Media|date=4 January 2020|work=The Guardian|access-date=10 January 2020|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nLong-Bailey announced that she would stand in an article for ''[[Tribune (magazine)|Tribune]]'' magazine on 6 January.<ref name=\"standard1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/rebecca-longbailey-enters-labour-leadership-race-a4327946.html|title=Rebecca Long-Bailey enters Labour leadership race|date=6 January 2020|access-date= 13 January 2020|work=Evening Standard|author= Morrison, Sean}}</ref> Long-Bailey is seen by many observers and party colleagues as the continuity candidate who would continue to take the party in the same direction as Corbyn.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.sky.com/story/labour-leadership-contest-rebecca-long-bailey-says-she-is-nobodys-continuity-candidate-11902905|publisher=Sky News|date=7 January 2020|author=McGuinness, Alan|title=Corbyn loyalist running for Labour leadership denies being a continuity candidate |accessdate=14 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://inews.co.uk/news/politics/labour-leadership-contest-ian-murray-rebecca-long-bailey-continuity-corbyn-1362133|work=i News|date=10 January 2020|author=Morris, Nigel|title=Labour leadership contest: Ian Murray claims Rebecca Long-Bailey looks like 'continuity Corbyn'|accessdate=14 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.sky.com/story/labour-leadership-contest-tom-watson-dismisses-continuity-candidate-rebecca-long-bailey-11902299|publisher=Sky News|date=6 January 2020|author=Culbertson, Alix|title=Labour leadership contest: Tom Watson dismisses 'continuity candidate' Rebecca Long-Bailey|accessdate=14 January 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Paul Mason\"/> While she has disputed the description,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politico.eu/article/the-battle-to-succeed-labour-leader-jeremy-corbyn-is-more-than-just-that-keir-starmer-rebecca-long-bailey-emily-thornberry-lisa-nandy-jess-phillips/|title=The battle to succeed Jeremy Corbyn (and more besides)|accessdate=18 January 2020|first=Eleni|last=Courea|work=Politico|date=17 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/labour-s-rebecca-long-bailey-accused-of-staggering-hypocrisy-in-antisemitism-row-1.495125|work=The JC|title=Labour's Rebecca Long Bailey accused of 'staggering hypocrisy' in antisemitism row|first=Lee|last=Harpin|date=8 January 2020|accessdate=18 January 2020}}</ref> her campaign has stressed ideological continuity with Corbyn.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newstatesman.com/politics/uk/2020/01/what-labour-leadership-candidates-are-telling-grassroots-and-why|first=Patrick|last=Maguire|work=New Statesman|date=16 January 2020|title=What Labour leadership candidates are telling the grassroots \u2013 and why|accessdate=18 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newstatesman.com/politics/uk/2020/01/why-left-keeps-losing|first=John|last=Gray|date=15 January 2020|title=Why the left keeps losing|work=New Statesman|accessdate=18 January 2020}}</ref> She attracted attention for rating Corbyn ten out of ten as a politician.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/rebecca-long-bailey-jeremy-corbyn-labour-party-leader-mp-a9274291.html|title=Rebecca Long Bailey says Jeremy Corbyn's record as Labour leader is '10 out of 10'|date=7 January 2020|access-date = 13 January 2020|work=The Independent|author1= Woodcock, Andrew|author2=Buchan, Lizzie}}</ref> She called for constitutional reform to spread power more evenly across the country, including abolishing the [[House of Lords]].<ref name=\"Scottish independence\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.itv.com/news/2020-01-12/labour-leadership-hopeful-long-bailey-vows-to-abolish-house-of-lords/|title=Labour leadership hopeful Rebecca Long-Bailey vows to abolish House of Lords|date=12 January 2020|access-date=16 January 2020|publisher=ITV News}}</ref>\n\n===Nominations stage===\n;Parliamentary\nCandidates first needed to receive nominations from at least 5% of the party's MPs and MEPs to progress to the second round of nominations. Starmer won the support of enough MPs and MEPs to progress to the next round of nominations on 8 January, when he was also endorsed by the trade union [[Unison (trade union)|Unison]].<ref name=\"StarmerSufficient\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-51035448|title=Labour leadership: Unison endorses Sir Keir Starmer|date=8 January 2020|access-date=8 January 2020|publisher=BBC News}}</ref> The following day, Long-Bailey, Nandy and Phillips got enough MP and MEP nominations to progress.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/jan/09/labour-leadership-long-bailey-phillips-and-nandy-win-backing|title=Labour leadership: Long Bailey, Nandy and Phillips win backing|last=Mason|first=Rowena|date=9 January 2020|work=The Guardian|access-date=9 January 2020||issn=0261-3077}} {{registration}}</ref>\n\nThe deadline for PLP and EPLP nominations was 2.30 pm on 13 January.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/independentpremium/politics-explained/labour-leader-nominations-starmer-long-bailey-nandy-phillips-thornberry-a9280596.html|author=Rentoul, John|title=What happens after today's deadline for MP nominations for Labour leader?|work=The Independent|date=13 January 2020|access-date = 14 January 2020}} {{subscription}}</ref> Lewis, with only five nominations including himself, withdrew from the contest shortly before the deadline.<ref name=\"lewiswithdrawal\">{{cite news|url=https://news.sky.com/story/labour-leadership-clive-lewis-pulls-out-of-race-to-succeed-jeremy-corbyn-11907812|title=Labour leadership: Clive Lewis pulls out of race to succeed Jeremy Corbyn| first=Alan|last=McGuinness|date=13 January 2020|access-date=13 January 2020|publisher=Sky News}}</ref> Thornberry was also short of the required nominations at the beginning of the day, but managed to obtain enough to qualify less than ten minutes before the deadline, helped by MPs who had formerly nominated Lewis.<ref name=\"5Through\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-51089217|publisher=BBC News|title=Labour leadership: Five candidates through as nominations close|date=13 January 2020|accessdate=17 February 2020}}</ref> After the close of nominations, the party announced that Long-Bailey, Nandy, Phillips, Starmer and Thornberry would proceed to the next stage of the election.<ref>{{cite tweet| user=labourpress| number= 1216742215306874883| author=Labour Press Team|date=13 January 2020|access-date=13 January 2020|title=Leader candidates who will progress to the next stage of the election are: Rebecca Long-Bailey Lisa Nandy Jess Phillips Keir Starmer Emily Thornberry}}</ref> Starmer received 88 nominations, more than any other candidate, followed by Long-Bailey with 33 and Nandy with 31.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://inews.co.uk/news/politics/labour-leadership-nominations-list-candidates-election-race-next-party-leader-mps-1358995|title=Full list of MPs supporting each Labour leadership candidate|work=i News|author= Chaplain, Chloe|date = 13 January 2020|access-date=16 January 2020}}</ref> Phillips and Thornberry were each nominated by 23 MPs and MEPs, one more than the minimum requirement of 22. Shortly after these nominations were published, Starmer was heavily favoured in the betting odds.<ref name=\"5Through\" />\n\n;Constituencies and affiliates\n[[File:Nandy, Starmer and Long-Bailey, 2020 Labour Party leadership election hustings, Bristol.jpg|thumb|Nandy, Starmer and Long-Bailey at the Bristol hustings on 1 February 2020]]\nCorbyn-supporting group [[Momentum (organisation)|Momentum]] balloted its members on a proposal that the group endorse Long-Bailey (alongside Angela Rayner for deputy). Of the 7,395 respondents 70% backed Long-Bailey, but the organisation was criticised by commentators<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/political-parties/labour-party/news/109127/momentum-members-back-rebecca-long-bailey-and|title=Momentum members back Rebecca Long-Bailey and Angela Rayner Labour leadership team|work=PoliticsHome|date=16 January 2020|first=Kevin|last=Schofield|publisher=Dods Parliamentary Communications|accessdate=17 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/labour-leadership-momentum-member-ballot-deputy-candidates-a9283826.html|work=The Independent|title=Labour leadership: Momentum faces backlash over 'ludicrous' ballot of members|first=Ashley|last=Cowburn|date=15 January 2020|publisher=ESI Media|accessdate=17 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newstatesman.com/politics/uk/2020/01/labour-leadership-rebecca-long-bailey-backed-slight-majority-momentum-members|title=Labour leadership: Rebecca Long-Bailey backed by slight majority of Momentum members|work=New Statesman|first1=Tim|last1=Bale|first2=Paul|last2=Webb|date=15 January 2020|accessdate=18 January 2020}}</ref> and by some Momentum members for not giving the option to endorse other candidates.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/jan/23/labour-leadership-momentum-survive|date=23 January 2020|work=The Guardian|first=Kate|last=Proctor|title=Can Momentum survive after Jeremy Corbyn stands down?|accessdate=24 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nStarmer became the first candidate to qualify for the ballot on 20 January with his third affiliate nomination, from the [[Union of Shop, Distributive and Allied Workers]];<ref name=KSMakes>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-51183581|title=Sir Keir Starmer makes it on to Labour leadership ballot|accessdate=21 January 2020|date=20 January 2020|publisher=BBC News}}</ref> by that point, he was also leading in nominations from [[Constituency Labour Party|Constituency Labour Parties]] (CLPs). Phillips withdrew from the election on 21 January, saying that she was unable to unite the party.<ref name=\"JPQuits\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-51195059|title=Labour leadership: Jess Phillips quits race to succeed Jeremy Corbyn|date=21 January 2020|publisher=BBC News|access-date=21 January 2020}}</ref> Nandy became the second candidate to quality for the ballot on 22 January, having received backing from the GMB and National Union of Mineworkers unions and the Chinese for Labour socialist society.<ref name=\"NandyQual\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-51204554|title=Labour leadership: Nandy joins Starmer on final ballot|date=22 January 2020 |publisher=BBC News|access-date=22 January 2020}}</ref> Long-Bailey was the third candidate to qualify, following further trade union support.\n\nHowever, Thornberry failed to achieve enough nominations, falling just short of the required number of constituency party nominations and being eliminated on 15 February 2020.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/feb/14/labour-leadership-emily-thornberry-fails-to-make-it-on-to-ballot|first=Kate|last=Proctor|title=Labour leadership: Emily Thornberry fails to make it on to ballot|date=14 February 2020|work=The Guardian|accessdate=15 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n;Reported data breach\nThe Labour Party reported two members of Starmer's campaign to the [[Information Commissioner's Office]] on 6 February of hacking into the party's membership database. The campaign described the complaint as \"utter nonsense\". The campaign chair, [[Jenny Chapman]], suggested that the allegations were a result of the Starmer team alerting party officials the week before to a possible data breach by Long-Bailey's campaign, though there is no evidence that this occurred.\n\n===Membership ballot===\nThe first public hustings to feature the final three candidates was held in [[Glasgow]], [[Scotland]] on 15 February.<ref name=\"Scotland hustings\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-51514530|title=Labour leadership hustings: Party 'can't win' without success in Scotland|date=15 February 2020|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=17 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Candidates==\n===Nominated===\nThe following individuals were nominated by the necessary number of Labour MPs and MEPs as well as receiving backing from the required number of constituency parties or affiliated organisations to proceed to the final ballot before members.\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 120px;\" | Candidate\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 200px;\" | Born\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 300px;\" | Political office\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 180px;\" | Campaign\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 110px;\" | Announced\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 110px;\" | Nominated\n\n|- <!-- Rebecca Long-Bailey -->\n|[[File:Official portrait of Rebecca Long Bailey crop 2.jpg|100px]]<br/>{{Sortname|Rebecca|Long-Bailey}}\n|{{dts|1979|9|22|format=dmy}}<br>(age {{age nts|1979|9|22}})<br>[[Old Trafford (area)|Old Trafford]], [[Greater Manchester]]\n|[[Shadow Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy|Shadow business secretary]] {{small|(2017\u2013present)}}<br/>MP for [[Salford and Eccles (UK Parliament constituency)|Salford and Eccles]] {{small|(2015\u2013present)}}<br/>[[Shadow Chief Secretary to the Treasury]] {{small|(2016\u201317)}}<br/>[[HM Treasury|Shadow Treasury minister]] {{small|(2015\u201316)}}\n|[[File:RLB2020 logo.png|200x200px]]<br>[https://www.rebeccaforleader.org/ Website]\n|6 January 2020\n|29 January 2020\n\n|- <!-- Lisa Nandy -->\n|[[File:Official portrait of Lisa Nandy MP crop 2.jpg|100px]]<br/>{{Sortname|Lisa|Nandy|Lisa Nandy}}\n|{{dts|1979|8|9|format=dmy}}<br>(age {{age nts|1979|8|9}})<br>[[Manchester]], [[England]]\n|MP for [[Wigan (UK Parliament constituency)|Wigan]] {{small|(2010\u2013present)}}<br/>[[Shadow Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change|Shadow energy secretary]] {{small|(2015\u201316)}}\n|[[File:Lisa Nandy for leader logo.png|200px]]<br>[https://lisanandy.org/ Website]\n|3 January 2020\n|22 January 2020\n\n|- <!-- Keir Starmer -->\n| [[File:Official portrait of Keir Starmer crop 2.jpg|100px]]<br/> {{Sortname|Keir|Starmer}}\n|{{dts|1962|9|2|format=dmy}}<br>(age {{age nts|1962|9|2}})<br>[[Southwark]], [[London]]\n|[[Shadow Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union|Shadow Brexit secretary]] {{small|(2016\u2013present)}}<br/>MP for [[Holborn and St Pancras (UK Parliament constituency)|Holborn and St Pancras]] {{small|(2015\u2013present)}}<br/>[[Home Office|Shadow immigration minister]] {{small|(2015\u201316)}}\n|[[File:Keir Starmer leadership campaign 2020 logo.png|frameless|200x200px]]<br>{{url|https://keirstarmer.com|Website}}\n|4 January 2020\n|20 January 2020\n\n|}\n\n===Eliminated===\nEmily Thornberry failed to receive backing from the required number of constituency parties and affiliated organisations.\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 120px;\" | Candidate\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 200px;\" | Born\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 300px;\" | Political office\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 180px;\" | Campaign\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 110px;\" | Announced\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 110px;\" | Eliminated\n\n|- <!-- Emily Thornberry -->\n| [[File:Official portrait of Rt Hon Emily Thornberry MP crop 2.jpg|100px]]<br/>{{Sortname|Emily|Thornberry}}\n|{{dts|1960|7|27|format=dmy}}<br>(age {{age nts|1960|7|27}})<br>[[Guildford]], [[Surrey]]\n|[[Shadow First Secretary of State]] {{small|(2017\u2013present)}}<br/>[[Shadow Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs|Shadow foreign secretary]] {{small|(2016\u2013present)}}<br/>MP for [[Islington South and Finsbury (UK Parliament constituency)|Islington South and Finsbury]] {{small|(2005\u2013present)}}<br/>[[Shadow Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union|Shadow Brexit secretary]] {{small|(2016)}}<br/>[[Shadow Secretary of State for Defence|Shadow defence secretary]] {{small|(2016)}}<br/>[[Department for Work and Pensions|Shadow employment minister]] {{small|(2015\u201316)}}<br/>[[Shadow Attorney General for England and Wales|Shadow Attorney General]] {{small|(2011\u20132014)}}\n|[[File:Emily Thornberry for Labour Leader logo.png|frameless|200x200px]]<br>{{url|https://emilyforlabour.com/|Website}}\n|18 December 2019\n|15 February 2020\n|}\n===Withdrawn===\nThe following candidates withdrew either during the process to receive nominations from MPs and MEPs or during the process to receive nominations from constituency parties or affiliated organisations.\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 120px;\" | Candidate\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 200px;\" | Born\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 300px;\" | Political office\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 180px;\" | Campaign\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 110px;\" | Announced\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 110px;\" | Withdrew\n\n|- <!-- Clive Lewis[[Clive Lewis (politician)| ]]-->\n\n|[[File:Official portrait of Clive Lewis crop 2.jpg|100px]]<br/>{{Sortname|Clive|Lewis|Clive Lewis (politician)}}\n|{{dts|1971|9|11|format=dmy}}<br>(age {{age nts|1971|9|11|2020|01|13}})<br>[[London]], [[England]]\n|[[HM Treasury|Shadow treasury minister]] {{small|(2018\u2013present)}}<br/>MP for [[Norwich South (UK Parliament constituency)|Norwich South]] {{small|(2015\u2013present)}}<br/>[[Shadow Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy|Shadow business secretary]] {{small|(2016\u201317)}}<br/>[[Shadow Secretary of State for Defence|Shadow defence secretary]] {{small|(2016)}}\n|[[File:Clive Lewis for Leader.jpg|200px]]<br>[https://www.cliveforleader.com Website]\n|19 December 2019\n|13 January 2020\n\n|- <!-- Jess Phillips -->\n\n|[[File:Official portrait of Jess Phillips MP crop 2.jpg|100px]]<br/>{{Sortname|Jess|Phillips|Jess Phillips}}\n|{{dts|1981|10|9| format=dmy}}<br>(age {{age nts|1981|10|9}})<br>[[Birmingham]], [[England]]\n|MP for [[Birmingham Yardley (UK Parliament constituency)|Birmingham Yardley]] {{small|(2015\u2013present)}}\n|[[File:Jess Phillips leadership campaign 2020 logo.svg|frameless|200x200px]]<br>{{url|https://jessphillips.net|Website}}\n|3 January 2020\n|21 January 2020<br><small>(Endorsed [[Lisa Nandy|Nandy]])</small>\n\n|}\n\n=== Declined ===\nThe following individuals were discussed in the media as potential leadership candidates, but chose not to stand:\n* [[Diane Abbott]], [[Shadow Home Secretary]]<ref name=\"longbaileyendorsementsbegin\">{{cite news |last1=Mason |first1=Rowena |last2=Pidd |first2=Helen |title=Labour leadership race begins as senior figures back Rebecca Long-Bailey |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/dec/15/labour-leadership-race-begins-as-senior-figures-back-rebecca-long-bailey |accessdate=16 December 2019 |work=The Guardian |date=15 December 2019}}</ref> ''(endorsed Long-Bailey)''\n* [[Yvette Cooper]], chair of the [[Home Affairs Select Committee]] since 2016<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2020/jan/06/yvette-cooper-seven-things-labour-must-do-party-leader|title=Seven things Labour must do to win the next election |author=Cooper, Yvette|date=6 January 2020|work=The Guardian|access-date=6 January 2020|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> ''(endorsed Starmer)''<ref>{{cite tweet|user=YvetteCooperMP|last=Cooper|first=Yvette|number=1216717935227625473|title=Many good candidates saying important things, so difficult decision. But have decided to nominate @Keir_Starmer & @AngelaRayner as best combination to pull party back together & take on serious challenge of rebuilding @UKLabour across the country|date=13 January 2020|accessdate=20 January 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Barry Gardiner]], [[Shadow Secretary of State for International Trade|shadow international trade secretary]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/barry-gardinder-cancels-labour-leadership-bid-a4330911.html|title=Barry Gardiner rules himself out of Labour leadership bid... because he would not make it past the first round|first=Jacob|last=Jarvis|date=9 January 2010|work=Evening Standard|accessdate=20 January 2020}}</ref> ''(endorsed Long-Bailey)''<ref>{{cite tweet|user=BarryGardiner|last=Gardiner|first=Barry|number=1216701990786473984|title=Despite my plane back from the Climate Conference being 4 hours late \u2014 I have just managed to cast my nomination for @RLong_Bailey & @DawnButlerBrent I will be voting for @AngelaRayner for Deputy but she kindly agreed I should help get our friend over the magic number of 22|date=13 January 2020|accessdate=20 January 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Dan Jarvis]], MP for [[Barnsley Central (UK Parliament constituency)|Barnsley Central]], [[Sheffield City Region Combined Authority|Mayor of the Sheffield City Region]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-south-yorkshire-50906730|title=Labour leadership: Dan Jarvis considers joining race|date=24 December 2019|publisher=BBC News|access-date=24 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet|user=DanJarvisMP|last=Jarvis|first=Dan|number=1214585582938132480|title=I'm humbled by the messages of support, but I won't be putting myself forward to be @UKLabour leader because of my commitment to serve as @SCR_Mayor. I look forward to a comradely contest & working hard to support our party back into government|date=7 January 2020|access-date=7 January 2020}}</ref> ''(nominated Nandy)''\n* [[David Lammy]], former [[Department for Business, Innovation and Skills|universities minister]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/david-lammy-labour-leadership-jeremy-corbyn-a9269816.html|title=David Lammy rules himself out of Labour leadership contest|date=4 January 2020|work=The Independent|author= Kentish, Benjamin|access-date=4 January 2020}}</ref> ''(endorsed Starmer)''<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.itv.com/news/2020-01-08/labour-leadership-contest-nominations-sir-keir-starmer/|accessdate=20 January 2020|title=Labour leadership frontrunner Starmer hires ex-Corbyn aide as key strategic advisor|publisher=ITV News|date=8 January 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Ian Lavery]], [[Chairman of the Labour Party (UK)|Chair of the Labour Party]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/politics/ian-lavery-confirms-seriously-considering-21182414|title=Ian Lavery confirms he is 'seriously considering' a bid for Labour leadership|last=Bloom|first=Dan|date=29 December 2019|work=Mirror Online|access-date=29 December 2019}}</ref> ''(endorsed Long-Bailey)''<ref name=\"Lavery-down\">{{cite tweet|user=IanLaveryMP|author=Ian Lavery MP|number=1214322453436088321|title=I have just released a statement regarding the Leadership of the Labour Party. It has been truly humbling to receive so much support from our fantastic members and my @UKLabour colleagues. Please read the full statement below|date=6 January 2020|access-date=6 January 2020}}</ref>\n* [[John McDonnell]], [[Shadow Chancellor of the Exchequer|shadow chancellor]] ''(endorsed Long-Bailey)''<ref name=\"Sky-next\">{{cite news|url=https://news.sky.com/story/general-election-who-will-be-next-labour-leader-after-jeremy-corbyn-11884758|title=General election: Who will be next Labour leader after Jeremy Corbyn?|last=Allegretti|first=Aubrey|date=13 January 2020|publisher=Sky News|access-date=14 January 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Angela Rayner]], [[Shadow Secretary of State for Education|shadow education secretary]] ''([[2020 Labour Party deputy leadership election|running for deputy leader]], endorsed Long-Bailey)''<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/angela-rayner-labour-deputy-leader-election-tom-watson-brexit-long-bailey-a9272131.html|title=Angela Rayner says Labour 'must win or die' as she enters deputy leadership race|work=The Independent|author= Buchan, Lizzie|date=7 January 2020|access-date=8 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Nominations==\n{{Main|Nominations in the 2020 Labour Party leadership election}}\n\nCandidates first needed to be nominated by at least 10% (22) of current Labour MPs and MEPs, who comprise the [[Parliamentary Labour Party]] (PLP) and the [[European Parliamentary Labour Party]] (EPLP). Candidates who passed this threshold then need nominations from at least 5% (33) Constituency Labour Parties (CLPs), or at least three affiliates including at least two trades unions that together represent at least 5% of affiliated members.<ref name=\"NS-rules\"/>\n\nThe table below shows the number of nominations achieved by each candidate. A green background indicates that the candidate met the nomination requirements. A pink background indicates that the candidate withdrew from the contest.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:95%; text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"3\" |Candidate\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"3\" rowspan=2|First stage<br>Labour MPs and MEPs\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"5\"| Second stage\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"3\" |Constituency Labour Parties\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"2\" |Affiliates\n|-\n! style=\"width: 50px\" |Nominations<ref name=\"Noms\">{{cite web|url=https://labour.org.uk/people/leadership-2020-nominations/leadership-2020/|title=Leadership 2020|publisher=The Labour Party|accessdate=10 January 2020}}</ref>\n! style=\"width: 40px\" |%\n!\n! style=\"width: 50px\" |Nominations<ref name=WhichCLPs>{{cite web|url=https://www.newstatesman.com/politics/staggers/2020/01/which-clps-are-nominating-who-2020-labour-leadership-race|title=Which CLPs are nominating who in the 2020 Labour leadership race?|date=16 January 2020|work=New Statesman|accessdate=17 January 2020}}</ref><ref Name=LabListNoms>{{Cite web|url=https://labourlist.org/2020/01/rolling-list-clp-nominations-in-labours-2020-leadership-race/|title=Rolling list: CLP nominations in Labour's 2020 leadership race|date=16 January 2020|work=LabourList|url-status=live|access-date=27 January 2020}}</ref>\n! style=\"width: 40px\" |%\n!\n! style=\"width: 50px\" |Nominations<ref name=WhichCLPs/><ref Name=LabListNoms/>\n! style=\"width: 40px\" |\n|-{{yes2}}\n| style=\"width: 170px; text-align:left\" |[[Keir Starmer]]\n| {{Infobox political party/seats|88|212|{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}}}{{efn|Starmer did not formally nominate himself, therefore the Labour Party lists him as having received 88 nominations, whereas some reports of the contest list him as having received 89 nominations}}\n| {{percentage|88|212|1}}\n| {{aye}}\n| {{Infobox political party/seats|374|648|{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}}}\n| {{percentage|374|648|1}}\n| {{aye}}\n| {{Infobox political party/seats|15|32|{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}}}\n| {{aye}}\n|-{{yes2}}\n| style=\"width: 170px; text-align:left\" |[[Rebecca Long-Bailey]]\n| {{Infobox political party/seats|34|212|{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}}}\n| {{percentage|34|212|1}}\n| {{aye}}\n| {{Infobox political party/seats|164|648|{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}}}{{efn|Bradford West CLP's nomination was declared void due to procedural errors, so has not been counted}}\n| {{percentage|164|648|1}}\n| {{aye}}\n| {{Infobox political party/seats|7|32|{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}}}\n| {{aye}}\n|-{{yes2}}\n| style=\"width: 170px; text-align:left\" |[[Lisa Nandy]]\n| {{Infobox political party/seats|31|212|{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}}}\n| {{percentage|31|212|1}}\n| {{aye}}\n| {{Infobox political party/seats|72|648|{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}}}\n| {{percentage|72|648|1}}\n| {{aye}}\n| {{Infobox political party/seats|4|32|{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}}}\n| {{aye}}\n|-{{no2}}\n| style=\"width: 170px; text-align:left\" |[[Emily Thornberry]] ''(eliminated)''\n| {{Infobox political party/seats|23|212|{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}}}\n| {{percentage|23|212|1}}\n| {{aye}}\n| {{Infobox political party/seats|31|648|{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}}}\n| {{percentage|31|648|1}}\n| {{nay}}\n| {{Infobox political party/seats|0|32|{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}}}\n| {{nay}}\n|-{{no2}}\n| style=\"width: 170px; text-align:left\" |[[Jess Phillips]] ''(withdrawn)''\n| {{Infobox political party/seats|23|212|{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}}}\n| {{percentage|23|212|1}}\n| {{aye}}\n| {{Infobox political party/seats|0|648|{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}}}\n| {{percentage|0|648|1}} \n| \n| {{Infobox political party/seats|0|32|{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}}}\n|\n|-{{no2}}\n| style=\"width: 170px; text-align:left\" |[[Clive Lewis (politician)|Clive Lewis]] ''(withdrawn)''\n| {{Infobox political party/seats|5|212|{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}}}\n| {{percentage|5|212|1}}\n| \n| colspan=5 {{Not polled}}|\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" |Total nominations\n| {{Infobox political party/seats|198|212|{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}}}{{efn|Not including Lewis's nominations and not taking Starmer as having nominated himself}}\n| colspan=2| {{percentage|198|212|1}}\n| {{Infobox political party/seats|641|648|{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}}}{{efn|Not including Bradford West CLP's nomination}}\n| colspan=2|{{percentage|641|648|1}}\n| {{Infobox political party/seats|26|32|{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}}}\n| colspan=2|\n|-\n|}\n{{notelist}}\n\n==Timeline==\n===Overview===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"  style=\"float:right; margin:11px\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"|Candidate status\n|-\n| style=\"background:crimson;\"|\n| Nominated, on the membership ballot\n|-\n| style=\"background:#ff4c7f;\"|\n| Eliminated during the nominations stage\n|-\n| style=\"background:#b24c4c;\"|\n| Withdrew from the election\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"|Events\n|-\n| style=\"background:red;\"|\n| Corbyn announces his resignation\n|-\n| style=\"background:orange;\"|\n| Nominations from the PLP and EPLP close\n|-\n| style=\"background:yellow;\"|\n| First leadership hustings\n|-\n| style=\"background:#007f33;\"|\n| Nominations from CLPs and affiliates close\n|-\n| style=\"background:darkblue;\"|\n| Membership ballot opens\n|-\n| style=\"background:purple;\"|\n| Membership ballot closes\n|-\n| style=\"background:black;\"|\n| Result announced\n|}\n\n{{#tag:timeline|\nImageSize = width:750 height:auto barincrement:30\nPlotArea  = top:19 bottom:20 right:20 left:20\nAlignBars = early\n\nColors     =\n  id:canvas    value:gray(0.9)\n  id:lightline value:gray(0.8)\n  id:darkline  value:gray(0.3)\n  id:Nominated value:rgb(0.863,0.078,0.235)  # Nominated candidate\n  id:Eliminated value:magenta # Eliminated candidate\n  id:Withdrawn value:claret   # Withdrawn candidate\n# Link to more colors: http://ploticus.sourceforge.net/doc/color.html\n\nDefine $today = {{#time:d/m/Y}}\n\nDateFormat = dd/mm/yyyy\nPeriod     = from:12/12/2019 till:10/04/2020\nTimeAxis   = orientation:horizontal\nScaleMinor = gridcolor:lightline unit:month increment:1 start:01/01/2020\n\nBackgroundcolors = canvas:canvas\n\nBarData =\n bar:Long-Bailey\n bar:Nandy\n bar:Starmer\n bar:Thornberry\n bar:Phillips\n bar:Lewis\n\nPlotData=\n  width:12 fontsize:S textcolor:Black anchor:till shift:(20,-4)\n bar:Long-Bailey\n  from:06/01/2020 till:$today color:Nominated text:\"[[Rebecca Long-Bailey|Long-Bailey]]\"\n bar:Nandy\n  from:03/01/2020 till:$today color:Nominated text:\"[[Lisa Nandy|Nandy]]\"\n bar:Starmer\n  from:04/01/2020 till:$today color:Nominated text:\"[[Keir Starmer|Starmer]]\"\n bar:Thornberry\n  from:18/12/2019 till:14/02/2020 color:Eliminated text:\"[[Emily Thornberry|Thornberry]]\"\n bar:Phillips\n  from:03/01/2020 till:21/01/2020 color:Withdrawn text:\"[[Jess Phillips|Phillips]]\"\n bar:Lewis\n  from:19/12/2019 till:13/01/2020 color:Withdrawn text:\"[[Clive Lewis (politician)|Lewis]]\"\nLineData=\n    layer:front at:13/12/2019 width:1 color:red\n    layer:front at:13/01/2020 width:1 color:orange\n    layer:front at:18/01/2020 width:1 color:yelloworange\n    layer:front at:14/02/2020 width:1 color:teal\n    layer:front at:24/02/2020 width:1 color:darkBlue\n    layer:front at:02/04/2020 width:1 color:purple\n    layer:front at:04/04/2020 width:1 color:black\nTextData=\n    text:\"13 December\" pos:5,8 textcolor:black fontsize:S\n    text:\"24 February\" pos:430,8 textcolor:black fontsize:S\n    text:\"4 April\" pos:680,8 textcolor:black fontsize:S\n}}\n\n===2019===\n* 12 December: Labour loses 60 seats in the [[2019 United Kingdom general election]]\n* 13 December: [[Jeremy Corbyn]] announces his resignation as leader of the Labour Party effective the outcome of the 2020 leadership election\n* 18 December: [[Emily Thornberry]] announces her candidacy\n* 19 December: [[Clive Lewis (politician)|Clive Lewis]] announces his candidacy\n\n=== 2020 ===\n==== January ====\n* 3 January: [[Jess Phillips]] and [[Lisa Nandy]] announce their candidacies\n* 4 January: [[Keir Starmer]] announces his candidacy\n* 6 January: [[Rebecca Long-Bailey]] announces her candidacy\n* 7 January: Nominations from the [[Parliamentary Labour Party]] (PLP) and [[European Parliamentary Labour Party]] (EPLP) open<ref name=\"4 April\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-51000133 |title=Labour leadership: Result will be announced on 4 April |publisher=BBC News |date=6 January 2020|accessdate=6 January 2020}}</ref>\n* 13 January:\n** Lewis withdraws his candidacy\n** Parliamentary nominations close at 14:30; Long-Bailey, Nandy, Phillips, Starmer and Thornberry proceed to the next stage<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.guardian-series.co.uk/uk_national_news/18156997.emily-thornberry-scrapes-next-round-labour-leadership-race/|title=Emily Thornberry scrapes into next round of Labour leadership race|date=13 January 2020|agency=Press Association|work=East London and West Essex Guardian|accessdate=13 January 2020|publisher=Newsquest Media Group}}</ref>\n* 15 January: Nominations from [[Constituency Labour Party|constituency parties]] (CLPs) and affiliate organisations open\n* 18 January: The first leadership hustings is held in [[Liverpool]]\n* 20 January: Starmer receives the required number of nominations to progress to the membership ballot<ref name=KSMakes/>\n* 21 January: Phillips withdraws her candidacy<ref name=JPQuits/>\n* 22 January:\n** Nandy receives the required number of nominations to progress to the membership ballot<ref name=\"NandyQual\"/>\n** Phillips endorses Nandy\n* 29 January: Long-Bailey receives the required number of nominations to progress to the membership ballot<ref name=\"29 January\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-51302365 |title=Labour leadership: Rebecca Long-Bailey makes final ballot|publisher=BBC News |date=29 January 2020|accessdate=29 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== February ====\n* 12 February: The first televised debate is held during a special edition of ''[[Newsnight]]''<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/live/2020/feb/12/pmqs-boris-johnson-jeremy-corbyn-in-red-wall-seats-won-by-tories-to-lose-out-disproportionately-from-switch-to-universal-credit-report-finds-live-news|title=Labour leadership hustings: Starmer, Nandy, Long-Bailey and Thornberry debate on BBC Newsnight \u2013 live|date=12 February 2020|work=The Guardian|accessdate=17 February 2020}}</ref>\n* 15 February: Constituency and affiliate nominations close at midnight; Thornberry fails to receive the required number of nominations and is eliminated\n* 24 February: Labour Party members start receiving postal ballots and online voting forms\n\n==== April ====\n* 2 April: Voting closes at midday\n* 4 April: Result of the membership ballot announced. Winning candidate declared the new [[Leader of the Labour Party (UK)|Leader of the Labour Party]]<ref name=\"4 April\"/> and becomes [[Leader of the Opposition (United Kingdom)|Leader of the Opposition]]\n\n==Campaign platforms==\n===Long-Bailey===\nLong-Bailey created a four-point plan: 'Aspirational socialism'; empower the movement and raise trade union membership; a \"Democratic Revolution\" and; a \"Green Industrial Revolution\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Proctor |first1=Kate |title=Rebecca Long-Bailey sets out four-point plan for Labour |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/feb/14/rebecca-long-bailey-sets-out-plan-to-rebuild-labour-party |accessdate=24 March 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=14 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Rodgers |first1=Sienna |title=Long-Bailey reveals four-point \"path to power\" plan in bid to shake up leadership race |url=https://labourlist.org/2020/02/long-bailey-reveals-four-point-path-to-power-plan-in-bid-to-shake-up-leadership-race/ |accessdate=24 March 2020 |work=LabourList |date=13 February 2020}}</ref> Long-Bailey has promised that she will continue to develop the \"[[Green New Deal#In the UK|Green New Deal]]\" policies that she had introduced to the party's 2019 election manifesto.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://labourlist.org/2020/01/long-bailey-lets-build-a-movement-to-hit-the-2030-climate-target/|title=Long-Bailey: \"Let\u2019s build a movement to hit the 2030 climate target\"|work=LabourList|date=31 January 2020|last=Rodgers|first=Sienna |accessdate=15 February 2020}}</ref> On democratic reform, Long-Bailey called for constitutional reform to spread power more evenly across the country, including [[Reform of the House of Lords#Abolition|abolishing]] the [[House of Lords]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.itv.com/news/2020-01-12/labour-leadership-hopeful-long-bailey-vows-to-abolish-house-of-lords/|title=Labour leadership hopeful Rebecca Long-Bailey vows to abolish House of Lords|date=12 January 2020|publisher=ITV News|accessdate=15 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nLong-Bailey has stated that if she wins the leadership election the Labour Party will maintain its commitment to bring energy, water, rail and mail back into public ownership.<ref>{{cite news |first=Kevin|last=Schofield|date= 29 January 2020 |title= Rebecca Long-Bailey challenges Labour leadership rivals to back mass nationalisations |url= https://politicshome.com/news/uk/political-parties/labour-party/news/109476/rebecca-long-bailey-challenges-labour-leadership |work=PoliticsHome |accessdate=15 February 2020}}</ref> She has also supported open selection as a process of selection for Labour MPs.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/entry/rebecca-long-bailey-backs-mandatory-reselections-for-mps-in-bid-to-woo-labour-members_uk_5e272eadc5b63211761a61eb|title=Rebecca Long-Bailey Backs Open Reselections For MPs In Bid To Woo Labour Grassroots|date=21 January 2020|first=Rachel|last=Wearmouth|work=Huffington Post|accessdate=2 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nLong-Bailey and her platform have been described by the media as \"continuity Corbyn\" because of her closeness to Corbyn, [[Momentum (organisation)|Momentum]] and the left of the Labour party, although she rejected the label.<ref name=\"Vice-RLBAspire\">{{cite news |last1=Kale |first1=Sirin |title=Rebecca Long-Bailey Wants You to Know 'Socialism Is Aspiration' |url=https://www.vice.com/en_uk/article/n7j5xb/rebecca-long-bailey-labour-leadership-interview |accessdate=24 March 2020 |work=Vice |date=23 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"ES-CC?\">{{cite news |last1=Hazarika |first1=Ayesha |title=Continuity Corbyn? I follow my own path, says Long-Bailey |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/rebecca-longbailey-interview-labour-leadership-race-a4382071.html |accessdate=24 March 2020 |work=Evening Standard |date=9 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn response to the release of [[President of the United States|U.S. President]] [[Donald Trump]]'s [[Trump peace plan|peace plan]] to resolve the [[Israeli\u2013Palestinian conflict]], Long-Bailey criticised the proposals, stating that they would \"only perpetuate conflict\" and \"undermine rights of the Palestinian people\".<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite news|url=https://labourlist.org/2020/01/labour-leadership-candidates-slam-trumps-middle-east-peace-plan/|title=Labour leadership candidates slam Trump\u2019s Middle East \u201cpeace\u201d plan|date=29 January 2020|first=Elliot|last=Chappell|work=LabourList|accessdate=15 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[COVID-19 pandemic in the United Kingdom|Covid-19 pandemic]], Long-Bailey made several recommendations to the government. She advocated the government look at a [[universal basic income]] for all people in the United Kingdom regardless of wealth,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Honeycombe-Foster |first1=Matt |title=Rebecca Long-Bailey urges Boris Johnson to bring in universal basic income to help Brits through coronavirus crisis |url=https://www.politicshome.com/news/article/labours-rebecca-longbailey-urges-boris-johnson-to-bring-in-universal-basic-income-to-help-brits-through-coronavirus-crisis |work=PoliticsHome |date=19 March 2020 |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref> and to eliminate the five-week waiting time before claimants can receive [[Universal Credit]].<ref name=\"Vice-RLBAspire\"/> Later in March, she advocated a National Food Service, where workers from Royal Mail deliver basic goods like food, medicine and toiletries to households to reduce pressure on supermarkets.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Stone |first1=Jonathan |title=Rebecca Long-Bailey calls for National Food Service to help people in isolation |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/coronavirus-rebecca-long-bailey-national-food-service-self-isolation-a9418266.html |work=The Independent |date=23 March 2020 |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref> In an article, Long-Bailey advocated that the government buys shares in key industries and puts these shares into a \"social wealth fund\". She stated that: \"This crisis should make us realise that we\u2019re all connected \u2013 that the chief executive relies on the refuse worker, the corporate lawyer on the supermarket worker, and the politician on the nurse. And this realisation should power how we rebuild our economy when the crisis is over.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Long-Bailey |first1=Rebecca |title=Rebecca Long-Bailey: There's only one way to save the British economy from coronavirus |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/voices/coronavirus-economic-crash-bailout-2008-rebecca-long-bailey-a9429441.html |accessdate=27 March 2020 |work=The Independent |date=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Nandy===\nIn January, Nandy accused the [[Blair ministry|Blair]] and [[Brown ministry|Brown governments]] of continuing the \"consensus that [[Margaret Thatcher|Thatcher]] built\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/nandy-labour-leadership-blair-brown-thatcher-speech-a9295901.html|title=Lisa Nandy attacks Blair\u2019s New Labour for maintaining \u2018Thatcher consensus\u2019, in dramatic change of tone|date=22 January 2020|last1=Buchan|first1=Lizzy|last2=Woodcock|first2=Andrew|work=The Independent|accessdate=15 February 2020}}</ref> She criticised [[New Labour]] for being \"as tight as the Tories\". She called for \"a modern, empowering welfare state for the 21st century\".<ref name=\"austerity\">{{cite news|url=https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/political-parties/labour-party/tony-blair/news/109263/lisa-nandy-accuses-new-labour-being-\u2018|title=Lisa Nandy accuses New Labour of being \u2018as tight as the Tories\u2019 as she praises Jeremy Corbyn|first=Alain|last=Tolhurst|date=22 January 2020|work=PoliticsHome|accessdate=15 February 2020}}</ref> She has praised Corbyn for shifting party policy towards a position that opposes [[United Kingdom government austerity programme|austerity]]<ref name=\"austerity\"/> and has stated her intention to abolish [[Universal Credit]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2020/feb/04/claimants-scared-as-full-roll-out-of-universal-credit-is-delayed-again|title=Claimants 'scared' of universal credit as full rollout delayed again|first=Patrick|last=Butler|work=The Guardian|date=4 February 2020|accessdate=15 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/av/uk-politics-51206016/lisa-nandy-welfare-system-sees-people-as-problems|title=Lisa Nandy: Welfare system sees people as 'problems'|date=22 January 2020|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=15 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nDuring the party hustings held in [[Bristol]], Nandy argued that the [[Orders, decorations, and medals of the United Kingdom|honours system]] should have references to the [[British Empire]] removed, and instead replaced with 'Excellence'.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/feb/01/lisa-nandy-honours-system-british-excellence|title=Recognise British excellence not empire in honours system, says Nandy|work=The Guardian|first=Michael|last=Savage|date=1 February 2020|accessdate=15 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nNandy has defended [[Freedom of movement for workers in the European Union|free movement]] within the [[European Union]], while also arguing that concerns about its flaws should not be simply dismissed as \"racist anti-immigrant rhetoric\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newstatesman.com/politics/uk/2020/01/why-lisa-nandy-defending-free-movement|title=Why Lisa Nandy is defending free movement|first=Patrick|last=Maguire|work=New Statesman|date=15 January 2020|accessdate=15 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nNandy is opposed to [[Scottish independence]] and argued that Labour should \"look to [[Catalonia]] and [[Quebec]]\" as examples for dealing with \"divisive nationalism\",<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-51139519|title=Scottish independence: Labour candidate Lisa Nandy criticised for Catalonia remarks|date=16 January 2020|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=15 February 2020}}</ref> later clarifying that the party can learn from the [[Spanish Socialist Workers' Party|Socialist Party in Spain]] that has show how \"the cause of social justice has beaten divisive nationalism\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thenational.scot/news/18209674.listen-lisa-nandy-snp-wilfully-distorted-catalonia-comments/|title=LISTEN: Lisa Nandy: SNP wilfully distorted Catalonia comments|date=4 February 2020|work=The National|publisher=Newsquest Media Group |accessdate=11 February 2020}}</ref> She has said she wants [[Scottish Labour]] to be represented in the shadow cabinet<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-51227758|title=What does the next Labour leader think about Scotland?|date=28 January 2020|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=18 February 2020}}</ref> and has also pledged not to interfere in devolved policymaking, allowing Scottish Labour to decide their own approach to independence.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.heraldscotland.com/news/18208194.labours-lisa-nandy-pledges-not-interfere-scottish-independence-policy/|title=Labour's Lisa Nandy pledges not to interfere on Scottish independence policy|date=3 February 2020|work=The Herald|first=Martin|last=Williams|accessdate=15 February 2020}}</ref> She also stated that [[Federalism in the United Kingdom|British federalism]] would not resolve the political division between England and Scotland.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thenational.scot/news/uk-news/18208117.lisa-nandy-backs-scottish-labour-shape-indyref2-policy/|title=Lisa Nandy backs Scottish Labour to shape IndyRef2 policy|work=The National|date=3 February 2020|accessdate=15 February 2020|agency=Press Association}}</ref>\n\nIn February, [[2020 Labour Party deputy leadership election|deputy leadership]] candidate [[Richard Burgon]] proposed a \"Peace Pledge\" to ensure that the party would not support future military action unless its members vote in favour of such a policy.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://politicshome.com/news/uk/defence/news/109681/richard-burgon-vows-let-labour-members-veto-military-action-he-slams|title=Richard Burgon vows to let Labour members veto military action as he slams 'frustrated Churchill' MPs|first=Matt|last=Honeycombe-Foster|work=PoliticsHome|date=6 January 2020|accessdate=15 February 2020}}</ref> Nandy voiced her strong disapproval of the pledge. She argued that civilians in war zones could not afford to wait for such a ballot to pass and it was irresponsible to share such classified information.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/politics/lisa-nandy-says-couldnt-disagree-21446183|title=Lisa Nandy says she 'couldn't disagree with Richard Burgon more' over Labour members war veto|first=Oliver|last=Milne|date=6 February 2020|work=Mirror Online|accessdate=15 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn an interview with ''[[The Jewish Chronicle]]'', Nandy acknowledged that the party had lost the trust of the [[British Jews|British Jewish]] community as a result of its \"failure of leadership\" and poor handling of [[Antisemitism in the UK Labour Party|antisemitism]] in the Party. She also said that she believed that the word '[[Zionism]]' had become \"horribly distorted and weaponised\" by some in the party; Nandy denounced those who questioned Israel's [[Right to exist#Israel|right to exist]] and reiterated her view that advocating the [[Human rights in the State of Palestine|rights]] of [[Palestinians|Palestinian]] does not contradict support for Israel.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/labour-leadership-hopeful-lisa-nandy-speaks-to-the-jc-1.495948|title=Labour leader candidate Lisa Nandy blames 'failure of leadership' for inaction on antisemitism|first=Lee|last=Harpin|date=27 January 2020|work=The JC|accessdate=15 February 2020}}</ref> She has chaired [[Labour Friends of Palestine & the Middle East|Labour Friends of Palestine]] since 2018.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://labourlist.org/2018/12/lisa-nandy-my-plans-as-the-new-chair-of-labour-friends-of-palestine-the-middle-east/|title=Lisa Nandy: My plans as the new chair of Labour Friends of Palestine & the Middle East|last=Nandy|first=Lisa|date=20 December 2018|work=LabourList|accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nWhen she spoke to the ''[[Evening Standard]]'' in January, Nandy called on [[General Secretary of the Labour Party|party general secretary]] [[Jennie Formby]] to publish the evidence that had been submitted to the [[Equality and Human Rights Commission]], as part of the commission's investigation into institutional antisemitism in the party. She added that openness and transparency would necessary to rebuild trust with the British Jewish community.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/lisa-nandy-anti-semitism-scandal-secret-report-a4349066.html|title=Lisa Nandy demands Labour Party publishes in full secret report on the anti-Semitism scandal|first1=Joe|last1=Murphy|first2=Ayesha|last2=Hazarika|date=30 January 2020|work=Evening Standard|accessdate=15 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nNandy has said that she will conduct a \"fair recruitment process\" for parliamentary candidates and end the practice of [[parachute candidate|\"parachuting\"]] those favoured by the leadership. She criticised the centralised approach taken during the [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019 general election]], in which a number of candidates were \"imposed\" by Corbyn and his allies.<ref name=\"parachute\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/feb/06/council-chiefs-deserve-role-in-labour-shadow-cabinet-says-lisa-nandy|title=Lisa Nandy calls for end to Labour candidate selection 'stitch-ups'|first=Kate|last=Proctor|date=6 February 2020|work=The Guardian|accessdate=15 February 2020}}</ref> Nandy has also stated that she would end the practice of nominating peers to the [[House of Lords]]. This announcement came after the Labour Party controversially nominated [[John Bercow]], former [[Speaker of the House of Commons (United Kingdom)|Commons Speaker]], and [[Karie Murphy]], Corbyn's former chief of staff.<ref name=\"parachute\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/houses/lords/news/109180/jeremy-corbyn-puts-john-bercow-and-tom-watson-house-lords|title=Jeremy Corbyn puts John Bercow and Tom Watson into House of Lords|first=Alain|last=Tolhurst|date=19 January 2020|work=PoliticsHome|accessdate=15 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nDuring a speech in [[Bassetlaw (UK Parliament constituency)|Bassetlaw]], one of the \"[[Red wall (British politics)|red wall]]\" constituencies gained by the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservatives]] in 2019, Nandy announced that a future [[Official Opposition Shadow Cabinet (United Kingdom)|shadow cabinet]] led by her would involve the representation of local Labour councillors, giving a seat to the elected Leader of the [[Local Government Association]] Labour Group.<ref name=\"parachute\" /><ref name=\"CouncillorsNom\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/lisa-nandy-labour-leadership-councillors-nominate-candidates-a9320846.html|title=Lisa Nandy promises to let councillors nominate Labour leadership candidates|first=Andrew|last=Woodcock|work=The Independent|date=6 January 2020|accessdate=15 February 2020}}</ref> She also pledged that she would give councillors the right to nominate candidates in future leadership elections, just as [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MPs]] and [[Member of the European Parliament|MEPs]] had during the previous month.<ref name=\"CouncillorsNom\" />\n\nNandy has expressed opposition to open selection and in favour of the current method for selection of Labour MPs.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/labour-leadership-open-selections-rebecca-long-bailey-lisa-nandy-hustings-corbyn-a9312751.html|title=Labour leadership contenders Lisa Nandy and Rebecca Long-Bailey clash over MP selection|date=1 February 2020|first=Ashley|last=Cowburn|work=The Independent|accessdate=2 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Starmer===\nStarmer has positioned himself in opposition to [[United Kingdom government austerity programme|austerity]], stating that Corbyn was \"right\" to position Labour as the \"party of [[Anti-austerity movement|anti-austerity]]\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theneweuropean.co.uk/top-stories/keir-starmer-labour-leadership-right-to-take-radical-position-1-6444007|title=Labour was 'right' to take 'radical' position on austerity, says Keir Starmer|date=30 December 2019|first=Mia|last=Jankowicz|work=The New European|accessdate=15 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.itv.com/news/2020-01-11/labour-leadership-candidates-keir-starmer-rebecca-long-bailey/|date=11 January 2020|publisher=ITV News|title=Starmer vows to protect Labour left-wing radicalism as Momentum backs Long Bailey|accessdate=15 February 2020}}</ref> Starmer has indicated he will continue with the Labour policy of scrapping [[Tuition fees in the United Kingdom|tuition fees]]. He has also pledged to [[nationalization|renationalise]] the railways, [[Royal Mail]], water companies and the energy companies. Starmer has called for ending outsourcing in the NHS, local government and justice system.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://inews.co.uk/news/politics/keir-starmer-labour-leadership-election-abolish-tuition-fees-nationalisation-1477522/|title=Keir Starmer promises to abolish tuition fees and nationalise industries if he becomes PM|date=11 February 2020|first=Hugo|last=Gye|work=i News|accessdate=15 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2020, Starmer announced that he would continue the policy introduced under [[Shadow Chancellor of the Exchequer|shadow Chancellor]] [[John McDonnell]], to raise taxes on the top 5% of earners with incomes of more than \u00a380,000.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/labour-leadership-race-keir-starmer-pledges-to-raise-tax-on-high-earners-rb9qw879p|title=Labour leadership race: Keir Starmer pledges to raise tax on high-earners|date=2 February 2020|work=Sunday Times|last1=Wheeler|first1=Caroline|last2=Smyth|first2=Chris|accessdate=15 February 2020|via=The Times}} {{subscription}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/feb/02/starmer-labour-leadership-tax-pledge-long-bailey-corbyn|title=Starmer shifts left in attempt to crowd Long-Bailey out of Labour contest|work=The Observer|date=2 February 2020|first=Michael|last=Savage|accessdate=15 February 2020|via=The Guardian}}</ref>\n\nStarmer has argued that the party should propose the reintroduction of [[Freedom of movement for workers in the European Union|free movement]] within the [[European Union]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/jan/31/keir-starmer-labour-should-argue-for-return-of-free-movement-brexit|title=Keir Starmer: Labour should argue for return of free movement|first=Heather|last=Stewart|date=31 January 2020|work=The Guardian|accessdate=15 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn response to the release of Trump's peace plan to resolve the Israeli\u2013Palestinian conflict, Starmer described the proposals as \"inconsistent with international law and human rights protections\".<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\nStarmer has said he is \"not against the principle\" of open selection but has not indicated clear support or opposition to it.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://labourlist.org/2020/01/interview-with-keir-starmer-fatboy-slim-open-selections-trotskyism-and-more/|title=Interview with Keir Starmer: Fatboy Slim, open selections, Trotskyism and more|date=12 January 2020|first=Elliot|last=Chappell|work=LabourList|accessdate=2 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Hustings and debates==\n===Public hustings===\nSeveral [[husting]]s events took place throughout the campaign, for both leadership and deputy leadership candidates.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://inews.co.uk/news/politics/labour-leadership-hustings-party-leader-election-dates-cities-full-watch-live-stream-1368701|title=Labour leadership hustings: timetable of dates and cities for election events, and how to watch them live|work=i News|access-date=5 February 2020|first=Serina|last=Sandhu|date=19 January 2020}}</ref> Labour-organised hustings took place on weekends throughout January and February 2020, at 11 locations in [[Great Britain]]. No hustings were held in [[Northern Ireland]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://labour.org.uk/people/leadership-elections-hub-2020/leadership-elections-hustings/|title=Leadership Elections Hustings|publisher=The Labour Party|access-date=4 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Date !! Host !! Moderator !! Venue !! Map\n|-\n| 18 January 2020 || Labour Party || Liam Thorp<br /> <small>(Political Editor, ''[[Liverpool Echo]]'')</small> || [[ACC Liverpool|Arena and Convention Centre]],<br /> [[Liverpool]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/news/liverpool-news/echo-chair-labour-leadership-hopefuls-17585593|title=ECHO in the chair as Labour leadership hopefuls go head to head for the first time in Liverpool|author=Thorp, Liam|work=Liverpool Echo|date=17 January 2020|access-date=15 February 2020}}</ref> || rowspan=18|{{Location map+ |United Kingdom |float=right |width=450 |caption= |places=\n{{Location map~ |United Kingdom|lat=52.95|long=-1.15|label_size=80 |label='''[[Nottingham]]'''|position=right}}\n{{Location map~ |United Kingdom|lat=52.50786|long=-2.08983|label_size=80 |label='''[[Dudley]]'''|position=right}}\n{{Location map~ |United Kingdom|lat=53.4|long=-2.983333|label_size=80 |label={{lower|0.2em|'''[[Liverpool]]'''}}|position=left}}\n{{Location map~ |United Kingdom|lat=51.45|long=-2.583333|label_size=80 |label='''[[Bristol]]'''|position=right}}\n{{Location map~ |United Kingdom|lat=51.483333|long=-3.183333|label_size=80 |label='''[[Cardiff]]'''|position=left}}\n{{Location map~ |United Kingdom|lat=55.860916|long=-4.251433|label_size=80 |label='''[[Glasgow]]'''|position=right}}\n{{Location map~ |United Kingdom|lat=51.507222|long=-0.1275|label_size=80 |label='''[[London]]'''|position=right}}\n{{Location map~ |United Kingdom|lat=53.479444|long=-2.245278|label_size=80 |label='''[[Manchester]]'''|position=right}}\n{{Location map~ |United Kingdom|lat=52.583333|long=-0.25|label_size=80 |label='''[[Peterborough]]'''|position=right}}\n{{Location map~ |United Kingdom|lat=51.835115|long=-0.320761|label_size=80 |label='''[[Wyboston]]'''|position=left}}\n{{Location map~ |United 