 presidential\n| ongoing = yes\n| previous_election = 2016 Labour Party leadership election (UK)\n| previous_year = 2016\n| next_election = \n| next_year = \n| turnout = \n| election_date = {{Start and end dates|2020|02|24|2020|04|04|df=yes}}\n\n<!-- PLEASE DO NOT REORDER WITHOUT CONSENSUS ON TALK PAGE - nomination numbers are not a vote -->\n\n<!-- Rebecca Long-Bailey -->| image1 = Official portrait of Rebecca Long Bailey crop 2.jpg\n| image1_size = 160x160px\n| candidate1 = [[Rebecca Long-Bailey]]\n| colour1 = \n| popular_vote1 = \n| percentage1 = \n\n<!-- Lisa Nandy -->| image2 = Official portrait of Lisa Nandy crop 2.jpg\n| image2_size = 160x160px\n| candidate2 = [[Lisa Nandy]]\n| colour2 = \n| popular_vote2 = \n| percentage2 = \n\n<!-- Keir Starmer -->| image3 = Official portrait of Keir Starmer crop 2.jpg\n| image3_size = 160x160px\n| candidate3 = [[Keir Starmer]]\n| colour3 = \n| popular_vote3 = \n| percentage3 = \n\n| title = leader\n| before_election = [[Jeremy Corbyn]]\n| after_election = \n}}\nThe '''2020 Labour Party leadership election''' was triggered after [[Jeremy Corbyn]] announced his intention to resign as [[Leader of the Labour Party (UK)|leader]] of the UK's [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] following the party's defeat at the [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019 general election]]. It is being held alongside the [[2020 Labour Party deputy leadership election]].\n\nTo qualify for the ballot, candidates needed nominations from 10% (22) of the party's [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Members of Parliament]] (MPs) and [[Member of the European Parliament|Members of European Parliament]] (MEPs), followed by support from either 5% (33) of [[Constituency Labour Party|Constituency Labour Parties]] (CLPs), or from at least three affiliated groups, including two trades unions and representing at least 5% of affiliated members.\n\nFive candidates, [[Rebecca Long-Bailey]], [[Lisa Nandy]], [[Jess Phillips]], [[Keir Starmer]] and [[Emily Thornberry]] received sufficient nominations to proceed to the second round of nominations. Starmer had the most nominations from MPs and MEPs at 88, followed by Long-Bailey and Nandy with 33 and 31 nominations respectively. Phillips and Thornberry each received 23 nominations, one above the minimum threshold to proceed. \n\nThree candidates, Long-Bailey, Nandy and Starmer, received sufficient combined support from affiliates and constituency parties to proceed to the final ballot. Starmer received the most nominations from both CLPs and affiliates having received nominations from 374 CLPs and 15 affiliates, followed by Long-Bailey with 164 CLPs and seven affiliates, and finally Nandy with 72 CLPs and four affiliates.\n\n==Background==\n{{also|Labour Party leadership of Jeremy Corbyn}}\n[[Jeremy Corbyn]] was elected Labour Party leader in a [[2015 Labour Party leadership election (UK)|2015 leadership election]] and [[2016 Labour Party leadership election (UK)|re-elected leader in 2016]] after a challenge from [[Owen Smith]]. While Labour gained 30 seats in the [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017 general election]], it lost 60 seats in the [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019 election]], resulting in the party having its lowest number of seats in the [[House of Commons (United Kingdom)|House of Commons]] since [[1935 United Kingdom general election|1935]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.channel4.com/news/factcheck/factcheck-the-2019-general-election-explained-in-five-graphs|title=The 2019 general election explained in five graphs|first=Georgina|last=Lee|date=13 December 2019|work=Channel 4 News|accessdate=16 January 2020|department=FactCheck}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/uk/john-mcdonnell-to-quit-frontline-politics-following-labour-defeat-38784856.html|title=John McDonnell to quit frontline politics following Labour defeat|first=Sophie|last=Morris|date=13 December 2019|accessdate=16 January 2020|work=Belfast Telegraph}}</ref> Corbyn subsequently announced that he would resign as Labour Party leader after a \"process of reflection\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/election-2019-50766114|title=Jeremy Corbyn: 'I will not lead Labour at next election'|date=13 December 2019|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/entry/jeremy-corbyn-resigns-labour-leader-general-election-2019_uk_5df2fcbce4b04bcba181d10b|title=Jeremy Corbyn Announces He Will Resign As Labour Party Leader|first=Ned|last=Simons|date=13 December 2019|work=HuffPost UK|accessdate=13 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Procedure==\nThe election is being conducted under a pure [[one member, one vote]] (OMOV) system, using the [[instant-runoff voting]] electoral system with preferential balloting to calculate the result.<ref name=\"next leader\" /><ref name=\"Politics-rules\"/> Candidates will be elected by members and registered and affiliated supporters, who all receive a maximum of one vote, and all votes will be weighted equally. This means that, for example, members of Labour-affiliated trades unions need to register as affiliated Labour supporters to vote.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jul/10/labours-leadership-contest-what-do-the-rules-look-like|title=Labour leadership contest: what are the rules?|work=The Guardian|last=Elgot|first=Jessica|date=10 July 2016|accessdate=12 July 2016}}</ref> Members who joined before 20 January will be eligible to vote.<ref name=\"Politics-rules\">{{cite web|url=http://www.politics.co.uk/comment-analysis/2019/12/16/labour-leadership-election-who-can-vote-and-how-does-it-work|title=Labour leadership election: Who can vote and how does it work?|first=Luke|last=Akehurst|work=Politics.co.uk|date=16 December 2019|access-date=16 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nTo stand, candidates needed to be nominated by at least 10% of the combined membership of the [[Parliamentary Labour Party]] (PLP) and [[European Parliamentary Labour Party]] (EPLP), meaning 22 MPs and MEPs at the time. As a result, a maximum of nine candidates can stand. They also needed to be nominated by at least 5% of [[Constituency Labour Party|Constituency Labour Parties]] (CLPs), meaning at least 33 CLPs, or at least three party affiliates that consist of at least 5% of affiliate members including at least two trades unions.<ref name=\"next leader\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-50781341|title=Who will be Labour's next leader?|date=13 December 2019|publisher=BBC News|access-date=13 December 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"NS-rules\">{{cite web|url=https://www.newstatesman.com/politics/elections/2019/12/how-does-labour-leadership-election-work|title=How does the Labour leadership election work?|work=New Statesman|date=13 December 2019|access-date=13 December 2019|last=Bush|first=Stephen}}</ref> Affiliates consist of [[Labour Party (UK) affiliated trade union|affiliated trades unions]], [[Socialist society (Labour Party)|socialist societies]] and the [[Co-operative Party]].<ref name=\"NS-rules\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.instituteforgovernment.org.uk/explainers/labour-party-leadership-contests|title=Labour Party leadership contests|publisher=Institute for Government|access-date=14 January 2020|author1=Zodgekar, Ketaki|author2=Durrant, Tim|date=6 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe timetable for the election was set by the party's [[National Executive Committee]] (NEC) on 6 January 2020.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/live/2020/jan/06/labour-leadership-jess-phillips-clarifies-brexit-stance-saying-she-cant-see-party-backing-remain-at-next-election-live-news|title=Labour leadership: NEC decides contest to last three months, with result announced Saturday 4 April \u2013 live news|last=Sparrow|first=Andrew|date=6 January 2020|work=The Guardian|access-date=6 January 2020|last2=Carrell|first2=Severin|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nNominations from the [[Parliamentary Labour Party]] and [[European Parliamentary Labour Party]] opened on 7 January and closed on 13 January. Between 15 January and 15 February, [[Constituency Labour Party|constituency parties]] and affiliate organisations could nominate their preferred candidate. Applications to become a registered supporter opened on 14 January and closed on 16 January. Voting in the membership ballot opened on 24 February<ref>{{cite news|url=https://labourlist.org/2020/02/ballot-drop-delays-tv-debates-and-fresh-policies-labours-leadership-latest/| title=Ballot drop delays, TV debates and fresh policies \u2013 Labour\u2019s leadership latest|last=Rodgers|first=Sienna|date=6 February 2020|work=LabourList|accessdate=19 February 2019}}</ref> and closes at midday on 2 April. The result of the leadership election will be announced on 4 April.<ref name=\"4 April\"/> The [[party conference|special conference]] planned for the announcement of the election result was \"scaled-back\" on 12 March because of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Labour leadership announcement cancelled |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-parliaments-51860609 |accessdate=13 March 2020 |publisher=BBC News |date=12 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Campaign==\n===Announcements===\nImmediately following the 2019 general election, [[Keir Starmer]], the [[Shadow Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union]], was considered favourite to win the leadership election by the online gambling company [[Betfair]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/politics/who-next-labour-leader-runners-21087938| title=Runners and riders to replace Jeremy Corbyn as the next Labour leader|last=Smith|first=Mikey|date=13 December 2019|work=Mirror Online |accessdate=13 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/next-labour-leader-odds-who-will-replace-jeremy-corbyn-a4312901.html|title=Next Labour leader odds: Who will replace Jeremy Corbyn?|author= Brewis, Harriet|date=13 December 2019|work=Evening Standard|accessdate=13 December 2019}}</ref> [[Rebecca Long-Bailey]], the shadow business secretary, was considered another front runner.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.brisbanetimes.com.au/world/europe/jeremy-corbyn-to-resign-amid-devastating-uk-election-defeat-20191213-p53jlt.html|title=Jeremy Corbyn steps down amid devastating UK election defeat|last=Shields|first=Bevan|date=13 December 2019|work=Brisbane Times|access-date=13 December 2019}}</ref> Various other figures were considered as possible leadership candidates, including [[Lisa Nandy]], the MP for [[Wigan (UK Parliament constituency)|Wigan]], who said on 15 December 2019 that she was \"seriously thinking\" about running for the leadership.<ref name= Honeycombe-Foster/> On 29 December, Long-Bailey wrote an article for ''[[The Guardian]]'' declaring her interest in standing and laying out her strategy for a \"progressive patriotism\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2019/dec/29/rebecca-long-bailey-labour-party-britain|title=We can take the Labour party back into power. Here's how|first=Rebecca|last=Long-Bailey|date=29 December 2019|work=The Guardian|accessdate=6 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nSome party figures, including the former MP [[Caroline Flint]] and the MP [[Wes Streeting]], argued for a \"clean break\" from the previous leadership. However, [[Len McCluskey]], general secretary of [[Unite the Union]],  said that the next leader should \"carry on the tradition\", describing Long-Bailey and [[Angela Rayner]] as his preferred candidates.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/election-2019-50800997|title=Let the Labour leadership battle commence|last=Pienaar|first=John|date=15 December 2019|publisher=BBC News|access-date=15 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/labour-leadership-contest-corbyn-rebecca-long-bailey-emily-thornberry-a9247966.html| title=Labour leadership race threatens party civil war as MPs fear 'continuity Corbyn' figure|date=15 December 2019|access-date=15 December 2019|author1= Woodcock, Andrew|author2= Buchan, Lizzie|work=The Independent}}</ref> Party figures affiliated with Long-Bailey and MPs such as Corbyn, as well as centrist figures like [[Alastair Campbell]], encouraged supporters of their preferred candidates to join the party to vote in the leadership election.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cityam.com/labours-period-of-reflection-quickly-turns-into-heated-leadership-race/|title=Labour's period of reflection quickly turns into leadership race|first=Stefan|last=Boscia|date=15 December 2019|work=City AM|access-date=15 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/labour-party-jeremy-corbyn-general-election-jess-phillips-a4313736.html|author= Christian, Bonnie|title=Labour moderates plan influx of new members to 'rebuild' party|date=15 December 2019|work=Evening Standard|access-date=15 December 2019}}</ref> [[Roy Hattersley]], a former deputy leader of the party, wrote on 21 December that MPs should refuse to accept Long-Bailey if she were elected leader.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/dec/21/david-lammy-may-stand-labour-first-bame-leader|title=Lammy hints at bid to be Labour's first BAME leader|last=Helm|first=Toby|date=21 December 2019|work=The Observer|access-date=21 December 2019|via=The Guardian}}</ref>\n\nThe shadow foreign secretary, [[Emily Thornberry]], was the first to announce, on 18 December, that she was standing for the leadership.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.sky.com/story/emily-thornberry-enters-contest-to-replace-labour-leader-jeremy-corbyn-11889772|title=Emily Thornberry enters contest to replace Labour leader Jeremy Corbyn|publisher=Sky News|author= Heffer, Greg|date = 18 December 2019|access-date=19 December 2019}}</ref> She laid out her pitch in an article for ''[[The Guardian]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2019/dec/18/boris-johnson-labour-brexit-election-emily-thornberry|title=Labour gifted Boris Johnson his 'Brexit election'. We can't be so inept again|author=Thornberry, Emily|date=18 December 2019|work=The Guardian|accessdate=6 January 2020}}</ref> She said that her first priority would be to deal with [[Antisemitism in the UK Labour Party|antisemitism in the party]] by implementing recommendations from the [[Board of Deputies of British Jews]], the [[Jewish Labour Movement]] and the [[Equality and Human Rights Commission]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/jan/09/thornberry-corbyn-aides-dismissed-attacks-against-israeli-civilians|title=Thornberry: Corbyn aides dismissed attacks against Israeli civilians |last=Syal|first=Rajeev|date=9 January 2020|work=The Guardian|access-date=10 January 2020|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> She criticised Corbyn's senior advisers for overruling her as the [[Shadow Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs|shadow foreign secretary]] and for their strategic decisions in the 2019 general election.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://politicshome.com/news/uk/political-parties/labour-party/jeremy-corbyn/news/108762/emily-thornberry-attacks-jeremy|author= Schofield, Kevin|title=Emily Thornberry attacks Jeremy Corbyn advisers as she steps up Labour leadership bid|date=24 December 2019|work=PoliticsHome|access-date=13 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url= https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/emily-thornberry-i-would-be-best-labour-leader-to-defeat-boris-johnson-qjchk80nn|title=Emily Thornberry: I would be best Labour leader to defeat Boris Johnson |last3=Elliott|first3=Francis |first1=Oliver|last1=Wright |first2=Henry|last2=Zeffman |date=19 December 2019|work=The Times |access-date=10 January 2020|issn=0140-0460}} {{subscription}}</ref>\n\n[[Clive Lewis (politician)|Clive Lewis]], the shadow minister for sustainable economics, announced on 19 December that he would stand.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.sky.com/story/clive-lewis-joins-emily-thornberry-in-labour-leadership-contest-to-replace-jeremy-corbyn-11890839|author= Snuggs, Tania|title=Clive Lewis joins Emily Thornberry in Labour leadership contest to replace Jeremy Corbyn|publisher=Sky News|date= 20 December 2019|access-date=13 January 2020}}</ref> He said that as leader, he would give more democratic power in the party to its members.<ref>{{Cite news| url= https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/i-ll-give-labour-members-more-say-clive-lewis-throws-his-hat-in-stn66056q|title=I'll give Labour members more say: Clive Lewis throws his hat in|last=Zeffman|first=Henry|date=20 December 2019|work=The Times|access-date=10 January 2020 |issn=0140-0460}} {{subscription}}</ref> He argued that the party should work more with other political parties on the left, and proposed constitutional reforms including supporting [[proportional representation]] and [[reform of the House of Lords]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/jan/07/clive-lewis-to-beat-tories-labour-has-to-work-with-other-progressives|title=Clive Lewis: to beat Tories, Labour has to work with other progressives|last=Stewart|first=Heather|date=7 January 2020|work=The Guardian|access-date=10 January 2020|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://inews.co.uk/news/politics/clive-lewis-labour-leadership-candidates-pitch-monarchy-referendum-proportional-representation-1361933|author= Chaplain, Chloe|title=Clive Lewis's radical leadership pitch includes a referendum on the monarchy|work=i News|date = 10 January 2020|access-date=10 January 2020}}</ref> In January 2020, he proposed a referendum about the future of the [[British royal family]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-51062770|title=Labour's Lewis calls for Royal Family referendum|date=10 January 2020|publisher=BBC News|access-date=10 January 2020}}</ref> He was criticised for his response to claims against him of sexual harassment, for which he had been cleared by a disciplinary body within Labour, which \"seemed unapologetic\".<ref>{{Cite news| url= https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/aides-fear-clumsy-response-to-abuse-claims-rules-out-clive-lewis-wbth3nt8f|title=Aides fear 'clumsy' response to abuse claims rules out Clive Lewis| last=Pogrund|first=Gabriel| date=5 January 2020|work=The Sunday Times|access-date=10 January 2020|via=The Times}} {{subscription}}</ref>\n\n[[Jess Phillips]] announced her candidacy in [[Grimsby]] on 3 January 2020.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-50981713|title=Jess Phillips joins Labour leadership race|date=3 January 2020|publisher=BBC News|access-date=3 January 2020}}</ref> She criticised the party's approach to Brexit and [[Scottish independence]], saying that she was opposed to a second referendum on Scottish independence.<ref name=\"Scottish independence\">{{cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/jess-phillips-says-no-to-another-scottish-independence-referendum-vvbdrdzzt|title=Jess Phillips opposes another Scottish independence referendum|last=McLaughlin|first=Mark|date=8 January 2020|work=The Times|access-date=10 January 2020|issn=0140-0460}} {{subscription}}</ref> She said that she would be open to arguing for the UK to rejoin the [[European Union]].<ref>{{cite news| url= https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/jan/05/labour-leadership-jess-phillips-says-party-could-argue-to-rejoin-eu|title=Labour leadership: Jess Phillips says party could argue to rejoin EU|last=Stewart|first=Heather|date=5 January 2020|work=The Guardian|access-date=10 January 2020|issn=0261-3077}} </ref><ref name=\":1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/jess-phillips-willing-to-fight-for-britain-to-rejoin-eu-w7f86xbh0|title=Jess Phillips willing to fight for Britain to rejoin EU|last=Swinford|first=Steven|date=5 January 2020|work=The Sunday Times|access-date=10 January 2020|issn=0956-1382|via=The Times}} {{subscription}}</ref> Criticising the party's manifesto at the 2019 general election, Phillips said that she would support nationalising railways but would not prioritise further nationalisation.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nNandy announced that she would stand in a letter to the ''[[Wigan Post]]'' on the same day as Phillips.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wigantoday.net/news/politics/exclusive-wigan-mp-lisa-nandy-enters-the-race-to-become-new-leader-of-the-labour-party-1-10181778|title=Wigan MP Lisa Nandy enters the race to become new Leader of the Labour Party|author= Nowell, Andrew|work=Wigan Today|date = 3 January 2020 |access-date=3 January 2020}}</ref> She argued that the party needed a \"bridge\" to join areas in [[northern England]] where the party was losing seats and metropolitan areas where the party was gaining support.<ref name= Honeycombe-Foster>{{cite news|url=https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/political-parties/labour-party/news/108575/lisa-nandy-reveals-she-seriously-considering-run|title=Lisa Nandy reveals she is 'seriously considering' run for Labour leadership|last=Honeycombe-Foster|first=Matt|date=15 December 2019|work=PoliticsHome|access-date=14 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nStarmer, who a poll had indicated was the most popular potential candidate heading into the leadership election, announced his candidacy with a video posted to social media on 4 January followed by a launch in [[Stevenage]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-50995782|title=Keir Starmer enters Labour leadership contest|date=4 January 2020|publisher=BBC News|access-date=4 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/jan/04/keir-starmer-enters-labour-leadership-race|title=Keir Starmer to launch Labour leadership bid in Stevenage|agency=PA Media|date=4 January 2020|work=The Guardian|access-date=10 January 2020|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nLong-Bailey announced that she would stand in an article for ''[[Tribune (magazine)|Tribune]]'' magazine on 6 January.<ref name=\"standard1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/rebecca-longbailey-enters-labour-leadership-race-a4327946.html|title=Rebecca Long-Bailey enters Labour leadership race|date=6 January 2020|access-date= 13 January 2020|work=Evening Standard|author= Morrison, Sean}}</ref> Long-Bailey is seen by many observers and party colleagues as the continuity candidate who would continue to take the party in the same direction as Corbyn.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.sky.com/story/labour-leadership-contest-rebecca-long-bailey-says-she-is-nobodys-continuity-candidate-11902905|publisher=Sky News|date=7 January 2020|author=McGuinness, Alan|title=Corbyn loyalist running for Labour leadership denies being a continuity candidate |accessdate=14 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://inews.co.uk/news/politics/labour-leadership-contest-ian-murray-rebecca-long-bailey-continuity-corbyn-1362133|work=i News|date=10 January 2020|author=Morris, Nigel|title=Labour leadership contest: Ian Murray claims Rebecca Long-Bailey looks like 'continuity Corbyn'|accessdate=14 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.sky.com/story/labour-leadership-contest-tom-watson-dismisses-continuity-candidate-rebecca-long-bailey-11902299|publisher=Sky News|date=6 January 2020|author=Culbertson, Alix|title=Labour leadership contest: Tom Watson dismisses 'continuity candidate' Rebecca Long-Bailey|accessdate=14 January 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Paul Mason\"/> While she has disputed the description,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politico.eu/article/the-battle-to-succeed-labour-leader-jeremy-corbyn-is-more-than-just-that-keir-starmer-rebecca-long-bailey-emily-thornberry-lisa-nandy-jess-phillips/|title=The battle to succeed Jeremy Corbyn (and more besides)|accessdate=18 January 2020|first=Eleni|last=Courea|work=Politico|date=17 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/labour-s-rebecca-long-bailey-accused-of-staggering-hypocrisy-in-antisemitism-row-1.495125|work=The JC|title=Labour's Rebecca Long Bailey accused of 'staggering hypocrisy' in antisemitism row|first=Lee|last=Harpin|date=8 January 2020|accessdate=18 January 2020}}</ref> her campaign has stressed ideological continuity with Corbyn.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newstatesman.com/politics/uk/2020/01/what-labour-leadership-candidates-are-telling-grassroots-and-why|first=Patrick|last=Maguire|work=New Statesman|date=16 January 2020|title=What Labour leadership candidates are telling the grassroots \u2013 and why|accessdate=18 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newstatesman.com/politics/uk/2020/01/why-left-keeps-losing|first=John|last=Gray|date=15 January 2020|title=Why the left keeps losing|work=New Statesman|accessdate=18 January 2020}}</ref> She attracted attention for rating Corbyn ten out of ten as a politician.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/rebecca-long-bailey-jeremy-corbyn-labour-party-leader-mp-a9274291.html|title=Rebecca Long Bailey says Jeremy Corbyn's record as Labour leader is '10 out of 10'|date=7 January 2020|access-date = 13 January 2020|work=The Independent|author1= Woodcock, Andrew|author2=Buchan, Lizzie}}</ref> She called for constitutional reform to spread power more evenly across the country, including abolishing the [[House of Lords]].<ref name=\"Scottish independence\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.itv.com/news/2020-01-12/labour-leadership-hopeful-long-bailey-vows-to-abolish-house-of-lords/|title=Labour leadership hopeful Rebecca Long-Bailey vows to abolish House of Lords|date=12 January 2020|access-date=16 January 2020|publisher=ITV News}}</ref>\n\n===Nominations stage===\n;Parliamentary\nCandidates first needed to receive nominations from at least 5% of the party's MPs and MEPs to progress to the second round of nominations. Starmer won the support of enough MPs and MEPs to progress to the next round of nominations on 8 January, when he was also endorsed by the trade union [[Unison (trade union)|Unison]].<ref name=\"StarmerSufficient\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-51035448|title=Labour leadership: Unison endorses Sir Keir Starmer|date=8 January 2020|access-date=8 January 2020|publisher=BBC News}}</ref> The following day, Long-Bailey, Nandy and Phillips got enough MP and MEP nominations to progress.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/jan/09/labour-leadership-long-bailey-phillips-and-nandy-win-backing|title=Labour leadership: Long Bailey, Nandy and Phillips win backing|last=Mason|first=Rowena|date=9 January 2020|work=The Guardian|access-date=9 January 2020||issn=0261-3077}} {{registration}}</ref>\n\nThe deadline for PLP and EPLP nominations was 2.30 pm on 13 January.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/independentpremium/politics-explained/labour-leader-nominations-starmer-long-bailey-nandy-phillips-thornberry-a9280596.html|author=Rentoul, John|title=What happens after today's deadline for MP nominations for Labour leader?|work=The Independent|date=13 January 2020|access-date = 14 January 2020}} {{subscription}}</ref> Lewis, with only five nominations including himself, withdrew from the contest shortly before the deadline.<ref name=\"lewiswithdrawal\">{{cite news|url=https://news.sky.com/story/labour-leadership-clive-lewis-pulls-out-of-race-to-succeed-jeremy-corbyn-11907812|title=Labour leadership: Clive Lewis pulls out of race to succeed Jeremy Corbyn| first=Alan|last=McGuinness|date=13 January 2020|access-date=13 January 2020|publisher=Sky News}}</ref> Thornberry was also short of the required nominations at the beginning of the day, but managed to obtain enough to qualify less than ten minutes before the deadline, helped by MPs who had formerly nominated Lewis.<ref name=\"5Through\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-51089217|publisher=BBC News|title=Labour leadership: Five candidates through as nominations close|date=13 January 2020|accessdate=17 February 2020}}</ref> After the close of nominations, the party announced that Long-Bailey, Nandy, Phillips, Starmer and Thornberry would proceed to the next stage of the election.<ref>{{cite tweet| user=labourpress| number= 1216742215306874883| author=Labour Press Team|date=13 January 2020|access-date=13 January 2020|title=Leader candidates who will progress to the next stage of the election are: Rebecca Long-Bailey Lisa Nandy Jess Phillips Keir Starmer Emily Thornberry}}</ref> Starmer received 88 nominations, more than any other candidate, followed by Long-Bailey with 33 and Nandy with 31.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://inews.co.uk/news/politics/labour-leadership-nominations-list-candidates-election-race-next-party-leader-mps-1358995|title=Full list of MPs supporting each Labour leadership candidate|work=i News|author= Chaplain, Chloe|date = 13 January 2020|access-date=16 January 2020}}</ref> Phillips and Thornberry were each nominated by 23 MPs and MEPs, one more than the minimum requirement of 22. Shortly after these nominations were published, Starmer was heavily favoured in the betting odds.<ref name=\"5Through\" />\n\n;Constituencies and affiliates\n[[File:Nandy, Starmer and Long-Bailey, 2020 Labour Party leadership election hustings, Bristol.jpg|thumb|Nandy, Starmer and Long-Bailey at the Bristol hustings on 1 February 2020]]\nCorbyn-supporting group [[Momentum (organisation)|Momentum]] balloted its members on a proposal that the group endorse Long-Bailey (alongside Angela Rayner for deputy). Of the 7,395 respondents 70% backed Long-Bailey, but the organisation was criticised by commentators<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/political-parties/labour-party/news/109127/momentum-members-back-rebecca-long-bailey-and|title=Momentum members back Rebecca Long-Bailey and Angela Rayner Labour leadership team|work=PoliticsHome|date=16 January 2020|first=Kevin|last=Schofield|publisher=Dods Parliamentary Communications|accessdate=17 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/labour-leadership-momentum-member-ballot-deputy-candidates-a9283826.html|work=The Independent|title=Labour leadership: Momentum faces backlash over 'ludicrous' ballot of members|first=Ashley|last=Cowburn|date=15 January 2020|publisher=ESI Media|accessdate=17 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newstatesman.com/politics/uk/2020/01/labour-leadership-rebecca-long-bailey-backed-slight-majority-momentum-members|title=Labour leadership: Rebecca Long-Bailey backed by slight majority of Momentum members|work=New Statesman|first1=Tim|last1=Bale|first2=Paul|last2=Webb|date=15 January 2020|accessdate=18 January 2020}}</ref> and by some Momentum members for not giving the option to endorse other candidates.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/jan/23/labour-leadership-momentum-survive|date=23 January 2020|work=The Guardian|first=Kate|last=Proctor|title=Can Momentum survive after Jeremy Corbyn stands down?|accessdate=24 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nStarmer became the first candidate to qualify for the ballot on 20 January with his third affiliate nomination, from the [[Union of Shop, Distributive and Allied Workers]];<ref name=KSMakes>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-51183581|title=Sir Keir Starmer makes it on to Labour leadership ballot|accessdate=21 January 2020|date=20 January 2020|publisher=BBC News}}</ref> by that point, he was also leading in nominations from [[Constituency Labour Party|Constituency Labour Parties]] (CLPs). Phillips withdrew from the election on 21 January, saying that she was unable to unite the party.<ref name=\"JPQuits\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-51195059|title=Labour leadership: Jess Phillips quits race to succeed Jeremy Corbyn|date=21 January 2020|publisher=BBC News|access-date=21 January 2020}}</ref> Nandy became the second candidate to quality for the ballot on 22 January, having received backing from the GMB and National Union of Mineworkers unions and the Chinese for Labour socialist society.<ref name=\"NandyQual\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-51204554|title=Labour leadership: Nandy joins Starmer on final ballot|date=22 January 2020 |publisher=BBC News|access-date=22 January 2020}}</ref> Long-Bailey was the third candidate to qualify, following further trade union support.\n\nHowever, Thornberry failed to achieve enough nominations, falling just short of the required number of constituency party nominations and being eliminated on 15 February 2020.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/feb/14/labour-leadership-emily-thornberry-fails-to-make-it-on-to-ballot|first=Kate|last=Proctor|title=Labour leadership: Emily Thornberry fails to make it on to ballot|date=14 February 2020|work=The Guardian|accessdate=15 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n;Reported data breach\nThe Labour Party reported two members of Starmer's campaign to the [[Information Commissioner's Office]] on 6 February of hacking into the party's membership database. The campaign described the complaint as \"utter nonsense\". The campaign chair, [[Jenny Chapman]], suggested that the allegations were a result of the Starmer team alerting party officials the week before to a possible data breach by Long-Bailey's campaign, though there is no evidence that this occurred.\n\n===Membership ballot===\nThe first public hustings to feature the final three candidates was held in [[Glasgow]], [[Scotland]] on 15 February.<ref name=\"Scotland hustings\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-51514530|title=Labour leadership hustings: Party 'can't win' without success in Scotland|date=15 February 2020|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=17 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Candidates==\n===Nominated===\nThe following individuals were nominated by the necessary number of Labour MPs and MEPs as well as receiving backing from the required number of constituency parties or affiliated organisations to proceed to the final ballot before members.\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 120px;\" | Candidate\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 200px;\" | Born\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 300px;\" | Political office\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 180px;\" | Campaign\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 110px;\" | Announced\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 110px;\" | Nominated\n\n|- <!-- Rebecca Long-Bailey -->\n|[[File:Official portrait of Rebecca Long Bailey crop 2.jpg|100px]]<br/>{{Sortname|Rebecca|Long-Bailey}}\n|{{dts|1979|9|22|format=dmy}}<br>(age {{age nts|1979|9|22}})<br>[[Old Trafford (area)|Old Trafford]], [[Greater Manchester]]\n|[[Shadow Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy|Shadow business secretary]] {{small|(2017\u2013present)}}<br/>MP for [[Salford and Eccles (UK Parliament constituency)|Salford and Eccles]] {{small|(2015\u2013present)}}<br/>[[Shadow Chief Secretary to the Treasury]] {{small|(2016\u201317)}}<br/>[[HM Treasury|Shadow Treasury minister]] {{small|(2015\u201316)}}\n|[[File:RLB2020 logo.png|200x200px]]<br>[https://www.rebeccaforleader.org/ Website]\n|6 January 2020\n|29 January 2020\n\n|- <!-- Lisa Nandy -->\n|[[File:Official portrait of Lisa Nandy MP crop 2.jpg|100px]]<br/>{{Sortname|Lisa|Nandy|Lisa Nandy}}\n|{{dts|1979|8|9|format=dmy}}<br>(age {{age nts|1979|8|9}})<br>[[Manchester]], [[England]]\n|MP for [[Wigan (UK Parliament constituency)|Wigan]] {{small|(2010\u2013present)}}<br/>[[Shadow Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change|Shadow energy secretary]] {{small|(2015\u201316)}}\n|[[File:Lisa Nandy for leader logo.png|200px]]<br>[https://lisanandy.org/ Website]\n|3 January 2020\n|22 January 2020\n\n|- <!-- Keir Starmer -->\n| [[File:Official portrait of Keir Starmer crop 2.jpg|100px]]<br/> {{Sortname|Keir|Starmer}}\n|{{dts|1962|9|2|format=dmy}}<br>(age {{age nts|1962|9|2}})<